1
00:00:10,310 --> 00:00:11,910
(CHATTERING)

2
00:00:12,210 --> 00:00:14,610
MAN: Ten-hut!

3
00:00:14,810 --> 00:00:16,610
(SILENCE)

4
00:00:30,310 --> 00:00:35,410
(BUGLE PLAYS)

5
00:01:14,510 --> 00:01:16,110
Be seated.

6
00:01:16,310 --> 00:01:18,310
(SHUFFLING)

7
00:01:19,610 --> 00:01:21,810
Now, I want you to remember. . .

8
00:01:23,110 --> 00:01:27,010
. . .that no bastard ever won a war. . .

9
00:01:27,910 --> 00:01:30,310
. . .by dying for his country.

10
00:01:32,310 --> 00:01:33,910
He won it. . .

11
00:01:34,910 --> 00:01:39,710
. . .by making the other poor dumb bastard die for his country.

12
00:01:41,810 --> 00:01:43,210
Men. . .

13
00:01:45,110 --> 00:01:48,210
. . .all this stuff you've heard about America not wanting to fight. . .

14
00:01:48,410 --> 00:01:50,510
. . .wanting to stay out of the war. . .

15
00:01:51,010 --> 00:01:53,010
. . .is a lot of horse dung.

16
00:01:53,410 --> 00:01:54,710
Americans. . .

17
00:01:55,110 --> 00:01:57,510
. . .traditionally love to fight.

18
00:01:57,810 --> 00:02:03,010
All real Americans love the sting of battle.

19
00:02:04,810 --> 00:02:06,610
When you were kids. . .

20
00:02:08,110 --> 00:02:11,210
. . .you all admired the champion marble shooter. . .

21
00:02:11,410 --> 00:02:16,010
. . .the fastest runner, big-league ball players, the toughest boxers.

22
00:02:16,610 --> 00:02:19,110
Americans love a winner. . .

23
00:02:19,610 --> 00:02:22,210
. . .and will not tolerate a loser.

24
00:02:22,610 --> 00:02:24,910
Americans play to win all the time.

25
00:02:25,210 --> 00:02:30,210
I wouldn't give a hoot in hell for a man who lost and laughed.

26
00:02:30,910 --> 00:02:36,210
That's why Americans have never lost and will never lose a war. . .

27
00:02:37,010 --> 00:02:39,710
. . .because the very thought of losing. . .

28
00:02:40,710 --> 00:02:43,310
. . .is hateful to Americans.

29
00:02:44,810 --> 00:02:46,010
Now. . .

30
00:02:47,110 --> 00:02:50,310
. . .an army is a team.

31
00:02:51,110 --> 00:02:53,710
It lives, eats, sleeps, fights as a team.

32
00:02:54,010 --> 00:02:56,910
This individuality stuff is a bunch of crap.

33
00:02:57,110 --> 00:03:00,210
The bilious bastards who wrote that stuff about individuality. . .

34
00:03:00,410 --> 00:03:02,910
. . .for the Saturday Evening Post...

35
00:03:03,310 --> 00:03:07,910
. . .don't know anything more about real battle than they do about fornicating.

36
00:03:10,510 --> 00:03:14,410
Now we have the finest food and equipment. . .

37
00:03:15,510 --> 00:03:17,710
. . .the best spirit. . .

38
00:03:17,910 --> 00:03:20,410
. . .and the best men in the world.

39
00:03:21,810 --> 00:03:22,810
You know. . .

40
00:03:24,310 --> 00:03:28,710
. . .by God, I actually pity those poor bastards we're going up against.

41
00:03:28,910 --> 00:03:30,210
By God, I do.

42
00:03:30,410 --> 00:03:33,310
We're not just going to shoot the bastards. . .

43
00:03:33,810 --> 00:03:36,810
. . .we're going to cut out their living guts. . .

44
00:03:37,010 --> 00:03:40,910
. . .and use them to grease the treads of our tanks.

45
00:03:41,110 --> 00:03:46,010
We're going to murder those lousy Hun bastards by the bushel.

46
00:03:46,910 --> 00:03:48,110
Now. . .

47
00:03:49,410 --> 00:03:51,210
. . .some of you boys. . .

48
00:03:51,610 --> 00:03:53,810
. . .I know are wondering. . .

49
00:03:54,610 --> 00:03:58,510
. . .whether or not you'll chicken out under fire. Don't worry about it.

50
00:04:00,110 --> 00:04:02,110
I can assure you. . .

51
00:04:02,510 --> 00:04:04,810
. . .that you will all do your duty.

52
00:04:06,310 --> 00:04:08,210
The Nazis. . .

53
00:04:08,610 --> 00:04:10,610
. . .are the enemy.

54
00:04:10,910 --> 00:04:12,710
Wade into them!

55
00:04:13,210 --> 00:04:16,410
Spill their blood! Shoot them in the belly!

56
00:04:17,410 --> 00:04:19,810
When you put your hand. . .

57
00:04:20,510 --> 00:04:22,710
. . .into a bunch of goo. . .

58
00:04:23,010 --> 00:04:26,710
. . .that a moment before was your best friend's face. . .

59
00:04:29,010 --> 00:04:30,710
. . .you'll know what to do.

60
00:04:33,010 --> 00:04:35,410
There's another thing I want you to remember.

61
00:04:37,210 --> 00:04:42,010
I don't want to get any messages saying we are "holding our position. "

62
00:04:42,410 --> 00:04:45,910
We're not "holding" anything. Let the Hun do that.

63
00:04:46,510 --> 00:04:50,710
We're advancing constantly. We're not interested in holding on to anything. . .

64
00:04:51,010 --> 00:04:52,810
. . .except the enemy.

65
00:04:53,010 --> 00:04:56,810
We're going to hold on to him by the nose and kick him in the ass.

66
00:04:57,010 --> 00:04:59,310
We're going to kick the hell out of him all the time. . .

67
00:04:59,510 --> 00:05:03,210
. . .and we're going to go through him like crap through a goose!

68
00:05:05,510 --> 00:05:06,710
Now. . .

69
00:05:09,510 --> 00:05:11,310
. . .there's one thing. . .

70
00:05:11,910 --> 00:05:15,710
. . .that you men will be able to say when you get back home.

71
00:05:16,610 --> 00:05:18,810
And you may thank God for it.

72
00:05:20,610 --> 00:05:24,210
Thirty years from now when you're sitting around your fireside. . .

73
00:05:24,510 --> 00:05:27,010
. . .with your grandson on your knee. . .

74
00:05:28,110 --> 00:05:29,510
. . .and he asks you:

75
00:05:29,810 --> 00:05:33,210
"What did you do in the great World War ll?"

76
00:05:34,310 --> 00:05:36,310
You won't have to say:

77
00:05:38,210 --> 00:05:39,510
"Well. . .

78
00:05:40,910 --> 00:05:43,810
. . .I shovelled shit in Louisiana. "

79
00:05:46,910 --> 00:05:49,710
All right, now, you sons of bitches. . .

80
00:05:50,310 --> 00:05:52,210
. . .you know how I feel.

81
00:05:57,210 --> 00:05:59,310
I will be proud. . .

82
00:06:00,410 --> 00:06:04,510
. . .to lead you wonderful guys into battle anytime. . .

83
00:06:06,210 --> 00:06:07,610
. . .anywhere.

84
00:06:11,010 --> 00:06:12,510
That's all.

85
00:09:47,810 --> 00:09:50,810
(JEEPS RUMBLING)

86
00:10:37,710 --> 00:10:40,210
(DOG BARKS)

87
00:11:05,510 --> 00:11:07,810
The Arabs need food and clothing.

88
00:11:08,310 --> 00:11:11,210
They strip our dead before we can even bury them.

89
00:11:11,510 --> 00:11:14,310
Looks like the reports were pretty accurate.

90
00:11:17,110 --> 00:11:20,310
Sixty-one armored vehicles, 45 tons of ammunition. . .

91
00:11:20,610 --> 00:11:25,410
. . .twenty-five 40mm guns, three self-propelled 1 05s.

92
00:11:26,010 --> 00:11:28,410
Not counting mortars, machine guns, rifles. . .

93
00:11:28,610 --> 00:11:33,110
. . .pistols, telescopes, belt buckles, Gl socks.

94
00:11:34,710 --> 00:11:37,710
One thousand, eight hundred men.

95
00:12:06,110 --> 00:12:08,710
(CHEERING)

96
00:12:28,210 --> 00:12:29,410
(SPEAKS IN FOREIGN LANGUAGE)

97
00:12:34,310 --> 00:12:36,510
Our people salute you, general. . .

98
00:12:36,810 --> 00:12:40,910
. . .for your brilliant amphibious landing on the continent of Africa. . .

99
00:12:41,110 --> 00:12:44,810
. . .and for your enlightened administration of our country.

100
00:12:45,810 --> 00:12:47,410
I've enjoyed being here, Excellency.

101
00:12:47,610 --> 00:12:51,110
Naturally, I'd prefer to be in Tunisia fighting the Germans.

102
00:12:56,510 --> 00:12:58,810
(BAND PLAYS)

103
00:13:04,110 --> 00:13:08,010
"The lions in their dens tremble at his approach. "

104
00:13:09,710 --> 00:13:11,810
I appreciate that, Excellency.

105
00:13:12,010 --> 00:13:15,010
(BAND PLAYS)

106
00:14:14,210 --> 00:14:16,010
Magnificent!

107
00:14:16,410 --> 00:14:18,110
I wish our troops looked that good.

108
00:14:51,310 --> 00:14:55,110
Tell me, general, what do you think of Morocco?

109
00:14:55,410 --> 00:14:56,710
I love it, Excellency.

110
00:14:56,910 --> 00:15:01,410
It's a combination of the Bible and Hollywood.

111
00:15:45,310 --> 00:15:48,310
BRADLEY: These men fight at Kasserine? CARVER: Yes, sir.

112
00:15:48,510 --> 00:15:51,110
For the American Army to take a licking like that. . .

113
00:15:51,310 --> 00:15:54,010
. . .the first time at bat against the Germans. . . .

114
00:15:58,210 --> 00:16:01,110
Up against Rommel, what we need is the best tank man we've got.

115
00:16:01,310 --> 00:16:03,610
Somebody tough enough to pull this outfit together.

116
00:16:05,110 --> 00:16:07,510
-Patton? -Possibly.

117
00:16:08,410 --> 00:16:10,110
God help us.

118
00:16:10,410 --> 00:16:13,910
(SIREN WAILS)

119
00:17:33,510 --> 00:17:36,610
(SPEAKING IN ARABIC)

120
00:18:03,310 --> 00:18:04,710
Lieutenant. . .

121
00:18:05,110 --> 00:18:07,210
. . .where is the duty officer?

122
00:18:07,410 --> 00:18:08,610
Sir. . . .

123
00:18:08,910 --> 00:18:13,610
-He said he's caught at shaving. -Why isn't he here on duty?

124
00:18:14,110 --> 00:18:15,710
Guess he needed a shave.

125
00:18:16,010 --> 00:18:19,310
We got a new commanding general due today.

126
00:18:43,210 --> 00:18:44,010
(CRASHING)

127
00:18:44,210 --> 00:18:47,210
MAN: Who the hell is kicking me in the butt?

128
00:18:50,710 --> 00:18:52,410
Oh, sorry, sir.

129
00:18:52,710 --> 00:18:57,110
-What were you doing down there? -Trying to get some sleep, sir.

130
00:18:57,210 --> 00:18:58,810
Well. . . .

131
00:18:59,110 --> 00:19:00,110
Get back down there, son.

132
00:19:00,310 --> 00:19:03,510
You're the only son of a bitch here who knows what he's trying to do.

133
00:19:03,810 --> 00:19:05,410
Yes, sir.

134
00:19:09,210 --> 00:19:12,910
PATTON: Brad, how the hell are you? -Fine, George. Good to see you.

135
00:19:13,110 --> 00:19:15,910
We were all under the impression you wouldn't be here until 0900.

136
00:19:16,210 --> 00:19:18,110
Yes, I gathered that.

137
00:19:18,710 --> 00:19:21,710
-You know my boy, Dick Jenson. -Yes.

138
00:19:22,010 --> 00:19:24,110
Brad, tell me.

139
00:19:24,610 --> 00:19:28,010
-What are you doing here? -Ike wanted a report on Kasserine.

140
00:19:28,210 --> 00:19:30,810
Meanwhile, I have to stay here as an observer. . .

141
00:19:31,010 --> 00:19:33,010
. . .but I report directly to Ike.

142
00:19:33,110 --> 00:19:34,610
You're spying.

143
00:19:35,010 --> 00:19:37,510
Get me General Eisenhower's headquarters.

144
00:19:38,810 --> 00:19:40,810
Tell me, Brad. . .

145
00:19:42,010 --> 00:19:44,810
. . .what happened at Kasserine? I heard it was a shambles.

146
00:19:44,910 --> 00:19:47,510
Apparently, everything went wrong.

147
00:19:48,410 --> 00:19:52,410
We'd send over a 75mm shell, the krauts would return an 88.

148
00:19:52,610 --> 00:19:54,810
Their tanks are diesels.

149
00:19:55,410 --> 00:19:59,510
Even when we managed to hit one they kept on running. Our tanks. . . .

150
00:20:01,110 --> 00:20:02,910
The men call them "Purple Heart boxes. "

151
00:20:03,210 --> 00:20:05,710
One hot piece of shrapnel and the gasoline explodes.

152
00:20:06,010 --> 00:20:07,410
I warned them about the tank.

153
00:20:07,610 --> 00:20:10,310
I taIked to one of the soldiers about the half-tracks.

154
00:20:10,510 --> 00:20:14,010
I asked them if the machine-gun bullets pierced the armor.

155
00:20:14,310 --> 00:20:15,910
And he said, "No, sir.

156
00:20:16,110 --> 00:20:19,310
They just come through one side and rattle around a bit. "

157
00:20:20,310 --> 00:20:23,610
I understand they had a little trouble coordinating the air cover.

158
00:20:23,910 --> 00:20:25,310
The trouble was no air cover.

159
00:20:25,510 --> 00:20:29,010
-General Smith on the line, sir. -Excuse me, Brad.

160
00:20:34,710 --> 00:20:36,110
Bedell?

161
00:20:36,410 --> 00:20:40,710
Listen, I'm calling about Bradley and his job here.

162
00:20:41,410 --> 00:20:45,910
I need a good number-two man, I want to make Brad my deputy commander.

163
00:20:47,210 --> 00:20:49,010
You clear it with Ike?

164
00:20:50,110 --> 00:20:51,910
All right, thanks, Bedell.

165
00:20:52,210 --> 00:20:55,510
Now you're not spying for Eisenhower anymore, you're working for me.

166
00:20:56,310 --> 00:20:58,210
-Okay? -Fine, okay.

167
00:20:58,710 --> 00:21:01,910
Dick. You got those stars?

168
00:21:02,610 --> 00:21:04,810
-Yes, sir. -Let's get them on.

169
00:21:17,010 --> 00:21:20,210
What's the matter, Brad? I've been nominated by the president.

170
00:21:20,710 --> 00:21:25,010
I know, but it doesn't become official until it's approved by the Senate.

171
00:21:25,510 --> 00:21:27,010
Well. . .

172
00:21:27,610 --> 00:21:30,210
. . .they have their schedule and I have mine.

173
00:21:35,610 --> 00:21:36,710
George. . .

174
00:21:38,010 --> 00:21:41,110
. . .if you were named admiral of the Turkish Navy. . .

175
00:21:41,310 --> 00:21:43,610
. . .I believe your aides could dip into their haversacks. . .

176
00:21:43,810 --> 00:21:45,910
. . .and come up with the appropriate badge of rank.

177
00:21:47,010 --> 00:21:50,910
Anyway, congratulations. Premature congratulations.

178
00:21:52,110 --> 00:21:53,610
You know. . . .

179
00:21:54,310 --> 00:21:58,110
I think those stars look better on a green shirt.

180
00:21:58,410 --> 00:22:03,010
Did I ever tell you about the time I designed a uniform for tank crewmen?

181
00:22:04,610 --> 00:22:08,310
It was green leather, it had red stripes. . .

182
00:22:08,510 --> 00:22:12,310
. . .and sort of a row of brass buttons down across here.

183
00:22:12,610 --> 00:22:15,510
And topped off by a gold football helmet.

184
00:22:16,510 --> 00:22:19,110
The Army rejected it, of course.

185
00:22:19,310 --> 00:22:20,710
Goddamn, it was beautiful.

186
00:22:20,910 --> 00:22:22,010
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

187
00:22:22,310 --> 00:22:24,510
Lloyd Fredendall is just leaving.

188
00:22:58,610 --> 00:23:03,710
George, there's one other thing I put in my Kasserine report.

189
00:23:04,210 --> 00:23:06,810
Some of our boys were just plain scared.

190
00:23:07,110 --> 00:23:08,810
That's understandable.

191
00:23:09,010 --> 00:23:11,810
Even the best foxhound is gun-shy the first time out.

192
00:23:12,010 --> 00:23:13,710
I can remember. . .

193
00:23:14,410 --> 00:23:17,510
. . .when nothing frightened me as much as the idea of. . .

194
00:23:17,810 --> 00:23:19,210
. . .a bullet coming straight for my nose.

195
00:23:19,510 --> 00:23:23,610
I don't know why, but the image of a bullet coming right for my nose. . .

196
00:23:23,810 --> 00:23:26,110
. . .was more horrible than any other possibility.

197
00:23:26,310 --> 00:23:29,810
Well, I can understand that, with such a handsome nose.

198
00:23:31,910 --> 00:23:35,010
You want to know why this outfit got the hell kicked out of it?

199
00:23:35,310 --> 00:23:37,210
Blind man could see it in a minute.

200
00:23:37,710 --> 00:23:40,410
They don't look like soldiers. They don't act like soldiers.

201
00:23:40,710 --> 00:23:42,310
Why should they fight like soldiers?

202
00:23:42,510 --> 00:23:45,810
You're absolutely right. The discipline's pretty poor.

203
00:23:46,610 --> 00:23:49,810
ln about 1 5 minutes we're going to start turning these boys. . .

204
00:23:50,110 --> 00:23:52,710
. . .into fanatics, razors.

205
00:23:52,910 --> 00:23:55,410
They'll lose their fear of the Germans.

206
00:23:56,010 --> 00:23:58,910
I hope to God they never lose their fear of me.

207
00:24:19,510 --> 00:24:22,310
Up bright and early, general? Breakfast?

208
00:24:22,510 --> 00:24:24,710
Have all my officers finished breakfast?

209
00:24:24,910 --> 00:24:27,010
We're open from 6 till 8.

210
00:24:27,210 --> 00:24:29,610
Most of the officers are just coming in, sir.

211
00:24:29,910 --> 00:24:32,310
Please inform these officers the mess hall is closed.

212
00:24:33,110 --> 00:24:35,310
But, sir! It's only a quarter to 8.

213
00:24:35,610 --> 00:24:40,310
From now on, you will open at 6 and no one will be admitted after 6: 1 5.

214
00:24:40,510 --> 00:24:41,910
Where are your leggings?

215
00:24:42,210 --> 00:24:45,910
Leggings? Well, hell, general, sir, I'm a cook.

216
00:24:47,610 --> 00:24:49,210
You're a soldier.

217
00:24:50,210 --> 00:24:51,210
$20 fine.

218
00:24:56,210 --> 00:24:57,610
Gentlemen. . .

219
00:24:58,410 --> 00:25:00,510
. . .from this moment any man. . .

220
00:25:00,710 --> 00:25:03,810
. . .without leggings, without a helmet, without a tie. . . .

221
00:25:04,510 --> 00:25:07,910
Any man with unshined shoes or soiled uniform. . .

222
00:25:10,110 --> 00:25:11,810
. . .is going to be skinned.

223
00:25:51,810 --> 00:25:55,710
This is a barracks. It's not a bordello.

224
00:26:16,410 --> 00:26:19,310
(CHATTERING)

225
00:26:23,610 --> 00:26:25,610
-Good morning. -Good morning, sir.

226
00:26:26,510 --> 00:26:27,510
Doctor.

227
00:26:27,710 --> 00:26:28,810
Sir.

228
00:26:29,010 --> 00:26:33,310
I understand you have two cases of self-inflicted wounds.

229
00:26:33,510 --> 00:26:34,810
Yes, sir, we do.

230
00:26:35,110 --> 00:26:36,610
Get them out of here.

231
00:26:36,810 --> 00:26:39,210
One has developed a serious infection.

232
00:26:39,510 --> 00:26:42,610
I don't care if he dies, just get him out of here.

233
00:26:42,910 --> 00:26:46,310
Doesn't belong in the same room with men wounded in battle.

234
00:26:46,710 --> 00:26:49,410
-I'll see that they're moved. -One more thing.

235
00:26:49,810 --> 00:26:52,910
There'll be no "battle fatigue. " That's an order.

236
00:26:53,610 --> 00:26:56,510
Battle fatigue is a free ride to the hospital.

237
00:26:56,710 --> 00:26:58,810
I'm not going to subsidize cowardice.

238
00:26:59,110 --> 00:27:00,210
Yes, sir.

239
00:27:00,410 --> 00:27:03,810
Doctor. . . . Where's your helmet?

240
00:27:05,210 --> 00:27:07,710
I don't wear a helmet in the hospital.

241
00:27:08,610 --> 00:27:09,910
Start.

242
00:27:10,210 --> 00:27:13,210
I can't use my stethoscope when I'm wearing my helmet.

243
00:27:15,810 --> 00:27:17,110
Well. . .

244
00:27:18,810 --> 00:27:22,110
. . .then cut two holes in your helmet so that you can.

245
00:27:22,610 --> 00:27:25,910
And get those yellow-bellies out of here, today.

246
00:27:34,410 --> 00:27:35,710
Hold it.

247
00:27:36,510 --> 00:27:37,810
Turn right, here.

248
00:27:38,110 --> 00:27:40,110
The battlefield is ahead.

249
00:27:40,310 --> 00:27:42,610
Don't argue. I can smell a battlefield.

250
00:27:42,810 --> 00:27:44,410
He was out here yesterday.

251
00:27:44,710 --> 00:27:47,410
It's over there. Turn right, damn it.

