00:28:29,810 --> 00:28:31,410
It was here.

253
00:28:34,610 --> 00:28:36,410
The battlefield was here.

254
00:28:45,410 --> 00:28:48,510
The Carthaginians defending the city. . .

255
00:28:48,710 --> 00:28:52,010
. . .were attacked by three Roman legions.

256
00:28:53,910 --> 00:28:58,110
They were brave, but they couldn't hold. They were massacred.

257
00:29:00,610 --> 00:29:02,210
Arab women. . .

258
00:29:02,910 --> 00:29:06,810
. . .stripped them of their tunics and their swords and lances.

259
00:29:08,410 --> 00:29:10,410
The soldiers lay naked in the sun. . .

260
00:29:14,010 --> 00:29:15,810
. . .2000 years ago.

261
00:29:20,210 --> 00:29:21,810
I was here.

262
00:29:27,110 --> 00:29:28,510
You don't believe me.

263
00:29:32,110 --> 00:29:33,910
You know what the poet said:

264
00:29:35,210 --> 00:29:37,510
"Through the travail of ages

265
00:29:39,010 --> 00:29:42,310
It's the pomp and toils of war

266
00:29:42,810 --> 00:29:47,210
Have I fought and strove and perished

267
00:29:47,810 --> 00:29:50,410
Countless times upon the star

268
00:29:55,210 --> 00:29:58,110
As if through a glass and darkly

269
00:29:59,210 --> 00:30:01,910
The age-old strife I see

270
00:30:03,210 --> 00:30:06,010
Where I fought in many guises Many names

271
00:30:07,710 --> 00:30:09,310
But always me. "

272
00:30:16,410 --> 00:30:18,310
You know who the poet was?

273
00:30:21,110 --> 00:30:22,310
Me.

274
00:31:15,283 --> 00:31:19,079
Sir, the interrogation reports on the American prisoners...

275
00:31:19,329 --> 00:31:21,790
...captured in our victory at Kasserine.

276
00:31:23,834 --> 00:31:27,462
They are not very good soldiers, these Americans.

277
00:31:29,548 --> 00:31:31,550
I'm not so sure...

278
00:31:32,676 --> 00:31:34,678
...after only one battle.

279
00:31:36,847 --> 00:31:41,143
Their tanks were no match for our guns.

280
00:31:41,643 --> 00:31:43,770
And neither was their leadership, sir.

281
00:31:47,983 --> 00:31:51,737
At Kasserine they were not under American command.

282
00:31:51,987 --> 00:31:54,489
They were under the British General Anderson.

283
00:31:55,198 --> 00:32:00,620
British commanders and American troops... the worst of everything!

284
00:32:01,455 --> 00:32:05,292
I remind you that Montgomery is a British Commander.

285
00:32:06,168 --> 00:32:08,920
And he has driven us half way across Africa.

286
00:32:09,713 --> 00:32:13,717
Anyway, we have met the Americans for the first time and defeated them.

287
00:32:14,092 --> 00:32:15,761
I'm optimistic.

288
00:32:15,844 --> 00:32:18,930
You can afford to be an optimist, I can't.

289
00:32:31,310 --> 00:32:34,610
There's an opportunity for us to mount an offensive.

290
00:32:34,910 --> 00:32:36,910
We've concentrated on the flank. . .

291
00:32:37,210 --> 00:32:39,110
. . .draw strength from the British.

292
00:32:39,310 --> 00:32:41,610
It appears now that we could. . .

293
00:32:41,810 --> 00:32:43,710
. . .split the African corridor.

294
00:32:44,010 --> 00:32:45,410
Drive through Rommel to the sea.

295
00:32:45,710 --> 00:32:48,710
I'm sorry, but that territory has been reserved. . .

296
00:32:49,010 --> 00:32:51,210
. . .for General Bernard Law Montgomery.

297
00:32:51,510 --> 00:32:54,310
We're supposed to let him win this one no matter what.

298
00:32:54,610 --> 00:32:57,110
They're entitled to have their hero.

299
00:32:57,310 --> 00:33:00,610
Montgomery did push Rommel clear across North Africa.

300
00:33:00,910 --> 00:33:04,110
What about the Americans? Don't they need a hero too?

301
00:33:05,010 --> 00:33:06,610
You have anybody in mind?

302
00:33:08,910 --> 00:33:12,210
Air Vice-Marshal Coningham is here with General Buford.

303
00:33:12,510 --> 00:33:13,910
Excuse me, gentlemen. . .

304
00:33:14,110 --> 00:33:19,110
. . .while I ask our British friends what's happened to our air cover.

305
00:33:20,410 --> 00:33:21,810
BRADLEY: Harry.

306
00:33:22,110 --> 00:33:23,410
How are you?

307
00:33:23,610 --> 00:33:25,710
George. Good to see you.

308
00:33:27,310 --> 00:33:29,810
-You know Arthur Coningham. -Sir Arthur.

309
00:33:30,010 --> 00:33:31,510
Delighted to see you.

310
00:33:32,810 --> 00:33:34,810
I've heard so much about you.

311
00:33:39,610 --> 00:33:44,310
Gentlemen, it appears there's been a slight misunderstanding here. . .

312
00:33:44,610 --> 00:33:46,710
. . .and Ike thought we should fix it.

313
00:33:46,910 --> 00:33:49,010
No, no. No misunderstanding.

314
00:33:49,210 --> 00:33:52,110
We're supposed to have Allied air cover and we don't.

315
00:33:52,310 --> 00:33:55,010
German planes are strafing my troops.

316
00:33:55,310 --> 00:33:59,410
lf I may say so, general, I'm afraid your operation reports are inaccurate.

317
00:33:59,710 --> 00:34:03,310
Report? Three days ago, the crowds took off after my command car. . .

318
00:34:03,510 --> 00:34:05,310
. . .ran my ass into a ditch.

319
00:34:05,510 --> 00:34:08,610
My staff has assured me, we have complete air supremacy. . .

320
00:34:08,910 --> 00:34:10,610
. . .everywhere in the Mediterranean.

321
00:34:10,810 --> 00:34:12,910
PATTON: When I complained about air cover. . .

322
00:34:13,210 --> 00:34:15,910
. . .you said our troops were not battleworthy.

323
00:34:16,210 --> 00:34:21,010
You spoke of the discredited practice of using air force as an alibi. . .

324
00:34:21,310 --> 00:34:24,210
. . .for lack of success on the ground.

325
00:34:24,510 --> 00:34:28,110
I have to wet-nurse Montgomery, I don't have to stand for that.

326
00:34:28,410 --> 00:34:32,010
I sincerely apologize for that remark, whoever made it.

327
00:34:33,210 --> 00:34:35,810
And I promise you one thing, general:

328
00:34:36,110 --> 00:34:38,310
You will see no more German planes.

329
00:34:47,110 --> 00:34:49,010
(CHICKEN SQUAWKS)

330
00:34:50,510 --> 00:34:53,710
We were discussing air supremacy, Sir Arthur.

331
00:35:19,210 --> 00:35:20,510
(HORN HONKS)

332
00:35:20,710 --> 00:35:22,910
(GUNFIRE)

333
00:35:27,010 --> 00:35:28,310
Damn door won't open!

334
00:35:42,110 --> 00:35:44,310
By God, that's enough!

335
00:36:03,410 --> 00:36:05,510
Get that thing out of here!

336
00:36:06,410 --> 00:36:09,710
Come on, you bastards, take a shot at me on the nose!

337
00:36:09,910 --> 00:36:14,510
Get back in here, George! We need a corps commander, not a casualty.

338
00:36:41,310 --> 00:36:43,110
CONINGHAM: How'd you manage to stage that?

339
00:36:44,410 --> 00:36:45,610
I don't know. . .

340
00:36:45,810 --> 00:36:48,910
. . .but if I could find the Nazis flying those things. . .

341
00:36:49,110 --> 00:36:51,210
. . .I'd give them each a medal.

342
00:37:12,110 --> 00:37:15,110
PATTON: Can't get over how cold it gets in the desert.

343
00:37:15,810 --> 00:37:17,610
Awfully cold, sir.

344
00:37:48,310 --> 00:37:50,610
PATTON: Rommel's out there somewhere, waiting for me.

345
00:37:50,910 --> 00:37:52,310
JENSON: Yes, sir.

346
00:37:54,210 --> 00:37:55,610
PATTON: You know. . .

347
00:37:56,710 --> 00:38:01,010
. . .if I had my way, I'd send that genius son of a bitch. . .

348
00:38:01,410 --> 00:38:05,010
. . .an engraved invitation in iambic pentameter:

349
00:38:05,610 --> 00:38:09,110
A challenge in two stanzas to meet me alone in the desert.

350
00:38:09,710 --> 00:38:11,210
I'll deliver it.

351
00:38:14,810 --> 00:38:17,510
Rommel in his tank and me in mine.

352
00:38:18,610 --> 00:38:22,010
We'd stop about 20 paces. We'd get out, we'd shake hands. . .

353
00:38:22,910 --> 00:38:26,010
. . .then we'd button up and do battle, just the two of us.

354
00:38:27,310 --> 00:38:30,410
That battle would decide the outcome of the war.

355
00:38:31,310 --> 00:38:34,310
It's too bad jousting's gone out of style.

356
00:38:35,510 --> 00:38:37,310
It's like your poetry, general.

357
00:38:37,610 --> 00:38:40,210
It isn't part of the 20th century.

358
00:38:41,110 --> 00:38:42,910
You're right, Dick.

359
00:38:44,510 --> 00:38:46,410
The world grew up.

360
00:38:47,610 --> 00:38:49,210
Hell of a shame.

361
00:38:51,910 --> 00:38:55,110
Dick, I want a 24-hour guard put around this area.

362
00:38:55,310 --> 00:38:57,710
lf we don't, the Arabs will dig them up for their clothes.

363
00:38:58,010 --> 00:38:59,410
Yes, sir.

364
00:39:00,110 --> 00:39:04,010
Our graves aren't gonna disappear like everybody else's who fought here.

365
00:39:04,510 --> 00:39:08,810
The Greeks, Romans, Carthaginians.

366
00:39:11,310 --> 00:39:13,910
God, how I hate the 20th century.

367
