Old Alcibiades always went for the throat.

501
00:59:39,010 --> 00:59:41,010
I propose to take Sicily in the same way.

502
00:59:41,410 --> 00:59:44,410
-How's it going? -The old man has them in his pocket.

503
00:59:48,210 --> 00:59:50,010
PATTON: Now, according to my plan. . .

504
00:59:50,210 --> 00:59:53,210
. . .General Montgomery will land here.

505
00:59:54,610 --> 00:59:57,010
I'll hit the beaches here, take Palermo.

506
00:59:57,210 --> 01:00:00,610
Monty will drive north on the coast, I'll come due east. . .

507
01:00:00,810 --> 01:00:03,410
. . .take Messina and cut off the German escape route.

508
01:00:03,810 --> 01:00:05,410
Yes. . . .

509
01:00:05,810 --> 01:00:07,810
It looks like an interesting plan.

510
01:00:08,210 --> 01:00:11,610
Well, gentlemen, to the conquest of Sicily.

511
01:00:12,610 --> 01:00:13,610
ALEXANDER: To the conquest of Sicily.

512
01:00:14,410 --> 01:00:16,010
OFFICERS: To Sicily!

513
01:00:16,810 --> 01:00:20,010
George, you'd have made a great marshal for Napoleon. . .

514
01:00:20,210 --> 01:00:21,810
. . .if you'd lived in the 1 8th century.

515
01:00:22,210 --> 01:00:25,410
But I did, sir. I did.

516
01:01:02,210 --> 01:01:04,210
Morning. Is General Smith in?

517
01:01:04,610 --> 01:01:07,410
MAN: I believe he's in the lavatory. -Thank you.

518
01:01:14,810 --> 01:01:17,410
-Ah, there you are, Bedell. -Monty.

519
01:01:17,810 --> 01:01:21,610
Bedell, I've been giving a good bit of thought to the Sicily operation.

520
01:01:21,810 --> 01:01:23,010
Yes?

521
01:01:24,010 --> 01:01:25,410
I assume we're alone.

522
01:01:25,810 --> 01:01:29,010
Georgie Patton has already discussed his plan with Alexander.

523
01:01:29,410 --> 01:01:30,410
I realize that. . .

524
01:01:30,810 --> 01:01:34,610
. . .but I have an idea that his plan may lead to an absolute disaster.

525
01:01:35,010 --> 01:01:36,210
Oh?

526
01:01:40,010 --> 01:01:41,010
Bedell, look.

527
01:01:41,210 --> 01:01:43,410
This is Sicily.

528
01:01:44,210 --> 01:01:47,010
Now then, according to Patton's plan. . .

529
01:01:47,410 --> 01:01:49,810
. . .I will attack Syracuse here.

530
01:01:50,210 --> 01:01:52,610
And he would attack Palermo up here.

531
01:01:52,810 --> 01:01:55,210
Now, obviously our forces would be divided.

532
01:01:55,410 --> 01:01:58,010
And obviously, they could be chopped up piecemeal.

533
01:01:58,410 --> 01:02:02,810
Now then, what I propose, and what I shall insist on, by the way. . .

534
01:02:03,210 --> 01:02:04,410
. . .is this.

535
01:02:05,410 --> 01:02:06,410
(MONTGOMERY EXHALES)

536
01:02:06,610 --> 01:02:09,410
I will land at Syracuse as planned.

537
01:02:09,810 --> 01:02:13,410
But the Americans-- The Americans will land here, at Gela.

538
01:02:13,610 --> 01:02:18,410
I will advance north to Messina, the Americans protecting my flank.

539
01:02:19,010 --> 01:02:21,810
After all, Messina is the key.

540
01:02:22,210 --> 01:02:24,610
It's the reason for invading Sicily.

541
01:02:25,810 --> 01:02:28,410
I'll discuss your plan with Ike.

542
01:02:29,410 --> 01:02:32,210
I'm sure he'll give it serious consideration.

543
01:02:37,410 --> 01:02:38,810
-Amusing, isn't it? -What?

544
01:02:39,010 --> 01:02:40,810
That the plans for the invasion of Sicily. . .

545
01:02:41,010 --> 01:02:43,810
. . .should have been put forward in an Algerian lavatory.

546
01:02:44,410 --> 01:02:47,610
George, I have bad news for you about your Sicily plan.

547
01:02:47,810 --> 01:02:49,810
Ike has turned it down.

548
01:02:50,210 --> 01:02:54,610
Since the Italians will be defending their native soil for the first time. . .

549
01:02:55,010 --> 01:02:59,410
. . .and the German resistance is stiffening, we shouldn't be divided.

550
01:03:00,410 --> 01:03:04,010
-Well, where do my people land then? -In the Gulf of Gela.

551
01:03:04,410 --> 01:03:06,010
There's nothing there but a beach.

552
01:03:06,410 --> 01:03:10,210
Yes, but it puts you in a good position to support Montgomery.

553
01:03:11,410 --> 01:03:13,210
Where does Montgomery land?

554
01:03:13,410 --> 01:03:17,610
He'll land in Syracuse and drive north to Catania. Possibly even Messina.

555
01:03:18,210 --> 01:03:21,210
And you'll be alongside, protecting his left.

556
01:03:21,810 --> 01:03:22,810
I see.

557
01:03:24,810 --> 01:03:29,010
ln other words, we get the burden again while good old Monty gets the glory.

558
01:03:29,410 --> 01:03:32,210
Ike had to consider all points of view.

559
01:03:32,610 --> 01:03:35,810
He made his decision not as an American, but as an Ally.

560
01:03:36,810 --> 01:03:40,210
Had it been the other way around, I assure you, Monty would protest.

561
01:03:41,610 --> 01:03:42,810
No. . .

562
01:03:44,210 --> 01:03:46,410
. . .I've been in the Army 30 years.

563
01:03:47,010 --> 01:03:51,210
When I get an order, I say, "Yes, sir. " And I do my best to carry it out.

564
01:03:55,410 --> 01:03:59,410
This is what happens when your commander stops being an American. . .

565
01:04:00,010 --> 01:04:02,010
. . .and starts being an Ally.

566
01:04:13,760 --> 01:04:16,888
Here's the gangster Patton, landing at Gela with his Seventh Army.

567
01:04:17,514 --> 01:04:19,975
This film was captured after the landing.

568
01:04:24,646 --> 01:04:26,773
I didn't realize he was so tall.

569
01:04:27,691 --> 01:04:29,192
Over six feet.

570
01:04:38,618 --> 01:04:40,704
He's constantly giving personal commands.

571
01:04:40,912 --> 01:04:45,000
Obviously they now have two prima donnas in Sicily... Montgomery and Patton!

572
01:04:54,259 --> 01:04:56,428
There's another three-star general.

573
01:04:57,012 --> 01:05:00,432
General Bradley...Commander of the American II Corps.

574
01:05:00,890 --> 01:05:02,642
He looks like a common soldier.

575
01:05:03,393 --> 01:05:05,645
He is most capable, yet unpretentious.

576
01:05:05,937 --> 01:05:07,439
Unusual for a general.

577
01:05:09,524 --> 01:05:10,525
Sorry...

578
01:05:13,010 --> 01:05:15,210
I don't think I've made myself clear, sir.

579
01:05:15,610 --> 01:05:19,010
It's true, Montgomery met the toughest resistance there at Catania.

580
01:05:19,410 --> 01:05:20,210
However, if we're--

581
01:05:20,610 --> 01:05:22,010
Perfectly clear.

582
01:05:22,210 --> 01:05:26,010
Old Monty is as stuck as a bug on flypaper.

583
01:05:27,010 --> 01:05:29,210
But this order from General Alexander. . .

584
01:05:29,410 --> 01:05:33,210
. . .directing you to turn over the Vizzini-Caltagirone road to Montgomery.

585
01:05:33,810 --> 01:05:36,810
Well, then, old Bradley will have to slug-- slug, mind you. . .

586
01:05:37,210 --> 01:05:41,810
. . .his way up center of the island over those tough mountain roads, won't he?

587
01:05:42,210 --> 01:05:43,410
Yes, sir.

588
01:05:44,010 --> 01:05:45,810
Messina, Bell.

589
01:05:46,410 --> 01:05:47,410
Messina. . .

590
01:05:48,610 --> 01:05:51,410
. . .is the heart of it. lf they'd followed my plan, I'd be there by now.

591
01:05:51,810 --> 01:05:55,010
I'd cut off the retreat of every German on this island!

592
01:05:56,210 --> 01:05:58,210
Now, you know what I'm gonna do?

593
01:05:58,410 --> 01:05:59,810
I'm gonna go to Palermo.

594
01:06:00,010 --> 01:06:04,010
I'm gonna beat that limey at Messina if it's the last thing I ever do!

595
01:06:04,210 --> 01:06:08,410
Hey, what's all this talk about taking the Vizzini road away from 2nd Corps?

596
01:06:12,210 --> 01:06:15,010
General Alexander's orders. Road goes to Montgomery.

597
01:06:15,210 --> 01:06:17,810
Now, that road was assigned to me.

598
01:06:18,610 --> 01:06:21,410
How can I get north without it? You know the terrain there.

599
01:06:21,810 --> 01:06:25,810
I'm sorry, Brad. But Monty's run into tough opposition. Very tough.

600
01:06:28,410 --> 01:06:32,010
You wouldn't be taking advantage of this situation, would you?

601
01:06:32,410 --> 01:06:33,810
I don't know what you're talking about.

602
01:06:34,210 --> 01:06:37,210
Without that road, your army, except for my 2nd Corps. . .

603
01:06:37,410 --> 01:06:38,810
. . .would be out of a job.

604
01:06:39,410 --> 01:06:41,410
Free for you to go into Palermo.

605
01:06:41,810 --> 01:06:43,810
Who said anything about Palermo?

606
01:06:45,210 --> 01:06:47,010
I can read a map.

607
01:06:48,210 --> 01:06:50,610
Does Alexander know you've pushed out this far?

608
01:06:51,010 --> 01:06:53,410
That's a reconnaissance in force.

609
01:06:56,610 --> 01:06:57,810
George. . .

610
01:06:59,810 --> 01:07:02,010
. . .are you saying I've got to slug it out in those mountains. . .

611
01:07:02,410 --> 01:07:04,410
. . .with heavy resistance?

612
01:07:05,010 --> 01:07:07,810
Just so you can make a bigger splash than Monty?

613
01:07:08,610 --> 01:07:09,810
General. . .

614
01:07:10,810 --> 01:07:13,010
. . .I just follow my orders.

615
01:07:13,210 --> 01:07:15,610
Like the simple old soldier I am.

616
01:07:16,810 --> 01:07:18,210
General Bradley.

617
01:07:19,410 --> 01:07:22,210
Sir, General Alexander has heard we're moving west.

618
01:07:22,610 --> 01:07:26,810
He says here, "Stop immediately. Go no farther than Agrigento.

619
01:07:27,210 --> 01:07:30,010
Repeat. Stop, immediately. "

620
01:07:31,010 --> 01:07:33,010
That's what you think it says.

621
01:07:33,410 --> 01:07:36,210
I think it was garbled in transmission.

622
01:07:36,710 --> 01:07:39,110
Ask them to re-transmit the message.

623
01:07:39,410 --> 01:07:41,410
That'll take half a day at least.

624
01:07:41,810 --> 01:07:42,810
Yes, sir.

625
01:07:47,210 --> 01:07:48,610
Now, Brad.

626
01:07:51,410 --> 01:07:52,810
Where were we?

627
01:07:54,610 --> 01:07:57,210
We were talking about a simple. . .

628
01:07:57,610 --> 01:07:59,410
. . .old soldier.

629
01:08:29,810 --> 01:08:31,210
Look at that, gentlemen.

630
01:08:33,610 --> 01:08:35,210
Compared to war. . .

631
01:08:35,810 --> 01:08:39,010
. . .all other forms of human endeavor shrink to insignificance.

632
01:08:40,010 --> 01:08:42,210
Let's go, sergeant. Move out!

633
01:09:32,010 --> 01:09:34,010
Give me that helmet.

634
01:09:36,610 --> 01:09:38,410
Come on, let's get out of here!

635
01:09:50,710 --> 01:09:52,910
What silly son of a bitch is in charge of this operation?

636
01:09:53,410 --> 01:09:55,810
I don't know, but they ought to hang him.

637
01:10:08,010 --> 01:10:09,410
PATTON: Afternoon, Padre.

638
01:10:09,610 --> 01:10:12,210
PADRE: These men are here from the States, looking over our program. . .

639
01:10:12,610 --> 01:10:14,410
. . .for the spiritual welfare of the men.

640
01:10:14,610 --> 01:10:16,210
We'll take you right into Palermo.

641
01:10:16,610 --> 01:10:18,610
Col. David toured us around your quarters. . .

642
01:10:19,010 --> 01:10:23,410
. . .and I saw a Bible by your bed. Do you actually find time to read it?

643
01:10:24,410 --> 01:10:25,610
I sure do.

644
01:10:26,010 --> 01:10:27,810
Every goddamn day.

645
01:10:31,262 --> 01:10:32,889
Sir, the Americans have taken Palermo!

646
01:10:33,473 --> 01:10:34,599
Damn!

647
01:10:50,810 --> 01:10:53,210
Sir, Patton's taken Palermo!

648
01:10:54,610 --> 01:10:55,410
Damn!

649
01:10:55,610 --> 01:10:58,010
(CHEERING)

650
01:11:05,310 --> 01:11:08,110
(BAND PLAYS)

651
01:11:13,810 --> 01:11:16,210
Palermo's the most conquered city in history.

652
01:11:16,610 --> 01:11:18,410
First the Phoenicians. . .

653
01:11:19,010 --> 01:11:22,410
. . .the Romans, Carthaginians, Byzantines.

654
01:11:22,810 --> 01:11:24,410
Then came the Arabs. . .

655
01:11:24,810 --> 01:11:27,210
. . .Spaniards, Neapolitans.

656
01:11:27,410 --> 01:11:28,810
Now comes. . .

657
01:11:29,210 --> 01:11:31,010
. . .the American Army.

658
01:11:41,210 --> 01:11:43,210
This is from General Alexander, sir. . .

659
01:11:43,610 --> 01:11:46,610
. . .reminding you that you are not to take Palermo.

660
01:11:47,210 --> 01:11:49,210
Send him a message, Cod.

661
01:11:49,610 --> 01:11:51,810
Ask him if he wants me to give it back.

662
01:12:38,410 --> 01:12:40,010
PATTON: Let me ask you a question for a change.

663
01:12:40,410 --> 01:12:42,210
You've just come from Washington.

664
01:12:42,610 --> 01:12:45,010
How do they feel about our boys taking Palermo?

665
01:12:45,410 --> 01:12:49,410
The general impression is, your army barreled through token resistance. . .

666
01:12:49,810 --> 01:12:52,010
. . .while Montgomery faced the brunt of the fighting.

667
01:12:52,410 --> 01:12:55,010
Don't they know we took on the Hermann Göring division?

668
01:12:55,410 --> 01:12:56,810
Toughest outfit in the German Army.

669
01:12:57,010 --> 01:12:59,010
The people at home are interested in you.

670
01:12:59,410 --> 01:13:01,610
They're curious about your pearl-handle revolvers.

671
01:13:01,810 --> 01:13:04,810
They're ivory. Only a pimp from a New Orleans whorehouse. . .

672
01:13:05,210 --> 01:13:06,810
. . .would carry a pearl handle.

673
01:13:07,010 --> 01:13:08,610
What about your language?

674
01:13:09,010 --> 01:13:12,010
When I want it to stick, I give it to them loud and dirty.

675
01:13:12,210 --> 01:13:14,010
What do your troops feel about that?

676
01:13:14,410 --> 01:13:17,610
I don't want these men to love me. I want them to fight for me.

677
01:13:18,210 --> 01:13:22,010
Ernie Pyle says you have a secret weapon here: General Bradley.

678
01:13:22,410 --> 01:13:24,210
Ernie calls him "The GI General. "

679
01:13:24,610 --> 01:13:27,610
Omar Bradley is no secret. He's a damn fine commander.

680
01:13:27,810 --> 01:13:30,010
MAN: What's your feeling about Montgomery?

681
01:13:30,410 --> 01:13:32,410
PATTON: He's the best general the English have.

682
01:13:32,810 --> 01:13:36,210
He seems more concerned with not losing than he does about winning.

683
01:13:36,610 --> 01:13:39,610
He's not aggressive enough, is that correct?

684
01:13:40,210 --> 01:13:43,010
Look, I've been getting into a lot of trouble lately.

685
01:13:43,410 --> 01:13:46,210
Yesterday, the office told me that my Italian prisoners. . .

686
01:13:46,610 --> 01:13:48,210
. . .didn't have enough latrine.

687
01:13:49,010 --> 01:13:51,810
They didn't know what a latrine was till I showed them.

688
01:13:52,210 --> 01:13:55,410
lf I've said anything too critical of my British colleague. . .

689
01:13:55,810 --> 01:13:57,210
. . .let's forget about it.

690
01:13:57,410 --> 01:14:00,210
I will tell you one thing, though. Off the record.

691
01:14:01,210 --> 01:14:02,810
I'm gonna beat that. . .

692
01:14:03,210 --> 01:14:05,010
. . .gentleman to Messina.

693
01:14:13,210 --> 01:14:16,610
Ah, Freddie. Do you realize what this madman Patton is saying?

694
01:14:16,810 --> 01:14:19,010
He's going to save our skins by taking Messina.

695
01:14:19,410 --> 01:14:21,410
This report might interest you.

696
01:14:21,610 --> 01:14:25,210
Here I am in these bloody marshes, fighting malaria and Germans. . .

697
01:14:25,610 --> 01:14:28,810
. . .while he's taking Palermo and getting all the glory.

698
01:14:30,810 --> 01:14:31,810
Well!

699
01:14:32,010 --> 01:14:35,610
Now he's up against three good German divisions and he's stuck.

700
01:14:36,010 --> 01:14:37,810
He's not going to get Messina.

701
01:14:38,210 --> 01:14:41,410
That's reserved for the British 8th Army and me.

702
01:14:42,810 --> 01:14:44,610
(BOMBS EXPLODING)

703
01:14:48,210 --> 01:14:52,210
It's time for a move, Lucian. Terry Allen's 1 st Division is bogged down.

704
01:14:52,610 --> 01:14:54,210
You're bogged down too.

705
01:14:54,610 --> 01:14:57,810
What we need is another end run just to break things loose.

706
01:14:59,410 --> 01:15:02,410
-Lucian. How's my fighter? -Fine, George.

707
01:15:02,810 --> 01:15:06,810
Come in, come in. We need another one of your amphibious specialties.

708
01:15:10,210 --> 01:15:14,210
Lucian, I want you to send a reinforced battalion by sea. . .

709
01:15:14,610 --> 01:15:18,010
. . .to make a landing up here at Brolo behind the kraut lines.

710
01:15:18,210 --> 01:15:20,610
You want me to do a land-based attack.

711
01:15:21,010 --> 01:15:24,010
Right. I want a coordinated attack the morning of the 1 1 th.

712
01:15:24,610 --> 01:15:26,610
I don't think we can make it by the 11 th.

713
01:15:27,010 --> 01:15:31,610
-Hell, it's only 1 5, 20 miles. -My boys have been dying for yards.

714
01:15:32,810 --> 01:15:34,010
Hm.

715
01:15:34,410 --> 01:15:37,210
Maybe you better kick a few butts if you have to.

716
01:15:38,410 --> 01:15:41,210
I recommended you for your DSM in your last promotion.

717
01:15:41,610 --> 01:15:44,010
I know what you can do when you put your mind to it.

718
01:15:44,610 --> 01:15:46,210
Excuse me, sir.

719
01:15:47,610 --> 01:15:50,610
I'm sorry, but I can't do the impossible.

720
01:15:52,010 --> 01:15:55,610
You're too old an athlete to think you can postpone a scheduled match.

721
01:15:56,010 --> 01:15:59,410
You're an old athlete yourself. You know matches are postponed.

722
01:15:59,810 --> 01:16:03,810
lf we can't back Lucian up by land, our end run could be a disaster.

723
01:16:04,210 --> 01:16:08,010
Those men might get caught on the beach and cut to pieces.

724
01:16:08,410 --> 01:16:11,010
-What's the matter? BRADLEY: All we're saying is. . .

725
01:16:11,210 --> 01:16:13,810
. . .not to rush in until we're ready.

726
01:16:14,210 --> 01:16:15,810
Give him an extra day.

727
01:16:16,210 --> 01:16:17,410
Just one more day.

728
01:16:18,010 --> 01:16:19,810
The landing is on.

729
01:16:20,410 --> 01:16:21,610
We're going to Messina.

730
01:16:21,810 --> 01:16:25,210
We're going to get there before Montgomery does.

731
01:16:25,610 --> 01:16:29,810
-What's so important about that? -General Truscott. . .

732
01:16:30,410 --> 01:16:33,810
. . .if your conscience won't permit you to conduct this operation. . .

733
01:16:34,210 --> 01:16:35,810
. . .I'll find somebody who can.

734
01:16:36,010 --> 01:16:41,010
General, it's your privilege to relieve me anytime you want to.

735
01:16:41,410 --> 01:16:44,410
This match will not be postponed.

736
01:16:46,610 --> 01:16:47,810
Any questions?

737
01:16:53,810 --> 01:16:54,810
No, sir.

738
01:16:55,210 --> 01:16:57,810
You're a very good man, Lucian.

739
01:16:58,210 --> 01:17:00,810
You want to guard against being too conservative.

740
01:17:01,210 --> 01:17:03,210
Remember what Frederick the Great said:

741
01:17:03,610 --> 01:17:08,010
''L 'audace, I'audace! Toujours I'audace!''

742
01:17:10,410 --> 01:17:12,210
Go on, have a drink.

743
01:17:13,410 --> 01:17:18,210
Excuse me, sir, I won't be drinking for the next couple of days.

744
01:17:22,210 --> 01:17:25,610
lf anything happens to those men, I'd like to be there with them.

745
01:17:28,610 --> 01:17:31,010
You're not going, so forget about it.

746
01:17:32,810 --> 01:17:35,210
You believe Truscott's right?

747
01:17:36,010 --> 01:17:37,210
No.

748
01:17:39,010 --> 01:17:41,610
But you're gambling with those boys' lives. . .

749
01:17:41,810 --> 01:17:44,410
. . .just to beat Montgomery into Messina.

750
01:17:45,610 --> 01:17:48,810
lf you pull it off, you're a hero, but if you don't. . . .

751
01:17:49,810 --> 01:17:53,610
What happens to them? The ordinary combat soldier.

752
01:17:54,610 --> 01:17:58,410
He doesn't share in your dreams of glory, he's stuck here.

753
01:17:59,410 --> 01:18:04,010
He's living out every day, day-to-day, with death tugging at his elbow.

754
01:18:08,210 --> 01:18:11,210
There's one big difference between you and me, George.

755
01:18:13,210 --> 01:18:16,010
I do this job because I've been trained to do it.

756
01:18:16,810 --> 01:18:18,610
You do it because. . .

757
01:18:20,810 --> 01:18:22,410
. . .you love it.

758
01:18:38,410 --> 01:18:41,210
The men on the beach are catching hell, general.

759
01:18:41,410 --> 01:18:45,010
The men are doing their best. We have no replacements.

760
01:18:45,410 --> 01:18:47,810
I can't break through to the coast.

761
01:18:48,210 --> 01:18:50,010
I'm going down there myself.

762
01:19:05,210 --> 01:19:06,610
PATTON: Colonel!

763
01:19:07,810 --> 01:19:09,410
How did he get over there?

764
01:19:09,810 --> 01:19:11,610
PATTON: What the hell are you waiting for?

765
01:19:11,810 --> 01:19:15,210
Looking for a place to ford, general.

766
01:19:15,610 --> 01:19:17,410
I sent a patrol to reconnoiter.

767
01:19:17,810 --> 01:19:22,010
PATTON: I've done that. Down there this sewer's no more than 3 feet deep.

768
01:19:22,410 --> 01:19:25,410
Get that outfit cranked up or you'll be out of a job!

769
01:19:27,610 --> 01:19:30,610
-And put that helmet on. -Yes, sir.

770
01:19:45,810 --> 01:19:47,810
Move it! Let's go!

771
01:19:57,810 --> 01:20:01,210
-What's holding up this column? -I don't know, sir.

772
01:20:01,610 --> 01:20:02,610
Planes!

773
01:20:07,010 --> 01:20:08,410
Come on, move it!

774
01:20:31,810 --> 01:20:33,210
Pull up over there.

775
01:20:39,610 --> 01:20:41,210
-Come on. -What's going on here?

776
01:20:41,410 --> 01:20:42,410
Sir, these mules--

777
01:20:42,810 --> 01:20:43,810
Jackasses!

778
01:20:44,010 --> 01:20:48,410
You let a column get stalled and strafed on account of two jackasses?!

779
01:20:51,410 --> 01:20:52,610
(GUNSHOT)

780
01:20:53,010 --> 01:20:54,610
No. No.

781
01:21:02,410 --> 01:21:05,210
Now, dump them over the side and clear this bridge!

782
01:21:52,610 --> 01:21:55,210
We're pinned down because we can't get air support!

783
01:21:55,610 --> 01:21:57,610
Nobody's getting any air support!

784
01:21:57,810 --> 01:22:01,010
Put fire into this battalion, or I'll get somebody who can.

785
01:22:01,310 --> 01:22:02,510
Major!

786
01:22:03,010 --> 01:22:04,610
-You the executive officer here? -Yes, sir.

787
01:22:05,010 --> 01:22:06,210
-Your name? -WaIker.

788
01:22:06,610 --> 01:22:08,210
You're now commanding officer.

789
01:22:08,410 --> 01:22:10,810
You've got 4 hours to break through that beachhead.

790
01:22:11,010 --> 01:22:13,010
lf you don't make it, I'll fire you.

791
01:22:22,610 --> 01:22:27,210
50,000 men on this island would like to shoot that son of a bitch.

792
01:23:02,810 --> 01:23:06,010
Please take me home. Take me home.

793
01:23:07,010 --> 01:23:09,410
Please take me home. Take me home.

794
01:23:33,320 --> 01:23:38,320
-There he goes, "Old Blood and Guts. " -Yeah, our blood. His guts.

795
01:23:45,720 --> 01:23:47,120
Hi, how are you, son?

796
01:23:55,120 --> 01:23:56,920
Where are you from, Gomez?

797
01:23:58,320 --> 01:24:00,120
California, sir.

798
01:24:00,320 --> 01:24:01,920
Me too.

799
01:24:02,520 --> 01:24:06,320
-Where were you hit? -In the chest, sir.

800
01:24:07,120 --> 01:24:08,320
Well. . .

801
01:24:08,920 --> 01:24:13,720
. . .this might be interesting to you. The last German I saw had no chest.

802
01:24:14,320 --> 01:24:16,120
Didn't have any head either.

803
01:24:18,520 --> 01:24:20,320
You get well quickly, son.

804
01:26:16,520 --> 01:26:18,120
What's the matter with you?

805
01:26:21,920 --> 01:26:24,720
I guess I just can't take it, sir.

806
01:26:28,720 --> 01:26:30,120
What did you say?

807
01:26:33,520 --> 01:26:35,520
It's my nerves, sir.

808
01:26:36,920 --> 01:26:39,720
I just can't stand the shelling anymore.

809
01:26:42,520 --> 01:26:44,320
Your nerves?

810
01:26:46,120 --> 01:26:48,920
Hell, you're just a goddamn coward.

811
01:26:51,520 --> 01:26:52,920
Shut up!

812
01:26:55,120 --> 01:26:57,320
I won't have a yellow bastard crying. . .

813
01:26:57,920 --> 01:27:00,120
. . .in front of these brave, wounded men.

814
01:27:03,520 --> 01:27:04,920
Shut up!

815
01:27:07,720 --> 01:27:11,320
Don't admit this yellow bastard. Nothing wrong with him.

816
01:27:11,520 --> 01:27:16,120
I won't have sons of bitches afraid to fight stink up this place of honor.

817
01:27:16,920 --> 01:27:19,520
You're going back to the front, my friend.

818
01:27:19,720 --> 01:27:24,120
You may get shot, you may get killed, but you're going up to the fighting.

819
01:27:25,120 --> 01:27:28,520
Either that or I'll stand you up in front of a firing squad.

820
01:27:28,920 --> 01:27:32,920
I should shoot you myself, you bastard! Get him out of here!

821
01:27:35,520 --> 01:27:36,920
Send him up to the front!

822
01:27:37,120 --> 01:27:41,120
You hear me? You goddamn coward!

823
01:27:50,520 --> 01:27:52,520
I won't have cowards in my army.

824
01:28:23,120 --> 01:28:24,520
I had to kick a few butts. . .

825
01:28:24,720 --> 01:28:28,720
. . .but Truscott finally broke through to those people on the beach.

826
01:28:29,120 --> 01:28:31,320
Have you seen the casualty lists?

827
01:28:32,120 --> 01:28:33,520
Yes, I've seen them.

828
01:28:34,520 --> 01:28:36,120
What's the word from the coast road?

829
01:28:36,320 --> 01:28:39,120
The 3rd Division's east of Brolo, heading toward Messina.

830
01:28:39,320 --> 01:28:42,720
Let's get over there. I want to go in with the troops.

831
01:28:42,920 --> 01:28:45,920
You go ahead, George. I'm not very good at that.

832
01:28:48,120 --> 01:28:49,720
General Bradley. . .

833
01:28:49,920 --> 01:28:53,320
. . .it's time to consider how many casualties we'd have. . .

834
01:28:53,520 --> 01:28:56,920
. . .if we were still crawling on that goddamn road.

835
01:30:23,520 --> 01:30:25,520
Forward, march!

836
01:30:43,720 --> 01:30:45,720
Don't smirk, Patton. I shan't kiss you.

837
01:30:46,920 --> 01:30:51,720
Pity. I shaved close this morning to prepare for getting smacked by you.

838
01:31:00,920 --> 01:31:02,720
Forward, march!

839
01:31:37,720 --> 01:31:39,520
You wanted to see me, George?

840
01:31:42,520 --> 01:31:44,320
Got a letter here from Ike.

841
01:31:52,920 --> 01:31:56,120
I was rereading Caesar's Commentaries last night.

842
01:31:58,920 --> 01:32:03,520
In battle, Caesar wore a red robe to distinguish him from his men.

843
01:32:03,920 --> 01:32:06,320
I was struck by that fact because--

844
01:32:09,120 --> 01:32:12,720
"Despicable. " First time anybody's ever applied that word to me.

845
01:32:13,120 --> 01:32:17,120
Well, at least it's a personal reprimand, it's not official.

846
01:32:17,720 --> 01:32:21,120
The man was yellow. He should've been tried for cowardice and shot.

847
01:32:21,520 --> 01:32:25,720
People have taken a lot worse than a little kick in the pants.

848
01:32:26,120 --> 01:32:29,520
I ruffled his pride a bit. What's that compared to war?

849
01:32:30,320 --> 01:32:34,120
Two weeks ago at Palermo they said I was the greatest general. . .

850
01:32:34,720 --> 01:32:38,920
-. . .since Stonewall Jackson. -Now they draw cartoons about you.

851
01:32:39,120 --> 01:32:41,120
Dirty bastard!

852
01:32:41,520 --> 01:32:45,520
They got me holding a little Gl and kicking him with an iron boot.

853
01:32:45,920 --> 01:32:48,320
You see that, what's on my boot? A swastika.

854
01:32:48,920 --> 01:32:52,120
On my boot. An iron boot with a swastika!

855
01:32:56,520 --> 01:32:59,920
"You will apologize to the soldier you slapped. . .

856
01:33:00,520 --> 01:33:04,520
. . .to all doctors and nurses present in the tent at the time. . .

857
01:33:05,120 --> 01:33:07,920
. . .to every patient in the tent who can be reached. . .

858
01:33:08,520 --> 01:33:11,720
. . .and last but not least to the 7th Army as a whole. . .

859
01:33:12,120 --> 01:33:14,920
. . .through individual units, one at a time. "

860
01:33:20,320 --> 01:33:21,720
God, I. . .

861
01:33:23,520 --> 01:33:25,120
. . .feel low.

862
01:33:32,120 --> 01:33:33,720
PATTON: Oh, God...

863
01:33:33,920 --> 01:33:35,720
... Thou art my God.

864
01:33:36,720 --> 01:33:38,720
Early will I seek Thee.

865
01:33:39,520 --> 01:33:42,520
My soul thirsteth for Thee.

866
01:33:42,720 --> 01:33:47,120
My flesh longeth for Thee in a dry and thirsty land.

867
01:33:47,920 --> 01:33:51,320
So as I have seen Thee in the sanctuary.

868
01:33:51,720 --> 01:33:54,720
My soul followeth hard after Thee.

869
01:33:55,720 --> 01:33:59,520
But those that seek my soul to destroy it...

870
01:33:59,920 --> 01:34:03,320
...shall go into the lower parts of the earth.

871
01:34:04,120 --> 01:34:07,120
They shall fall by the sword.

872
01:34:07,520 --> 01:34:11,120
They shall be apportioned for foxes.

873
01:34:12,320 --> 01:34:15,320
But the king shall rejoice in God.

874
01:34:16,320 --> 01:34:19,520
Everyone that sweareth by him shall glory.

875
01:34:20,520 --> 01:34:24,720
But the mouth of them that speak lies...

876
01:34:25,520 --> 01:34:27,720
...shall be stopped.

877
01:34:32,120 --> 01:34:34,320
Ten-hut!

878
01:34:36,520 --> 01:34:37,720
PATTON: At ease.

879
01:34:50,320 --> 01:34:53,720
I thought I'd stand up here and let you people see. . .

880
01:34:55,720 --> 01:34:59,720
. . .if I am as big a son of a bitch as some of you think I am.

881
01:35:04,720 --> 01:35:07,320
I assure you I had no intention. . .

882
01:35:08,320 --> 01:35:12,120
. . .of being either harsh or cruel in my treatment of the. . .

883
01:35:12,720 --> 01:35:14,320
. . .soldier in question.

884
01:35:19,520 --> 01:35:22,120
My sole purpose was to try to restore in him. . .

885
01:35:22,320 --> 01:35:25,320
. . .some appreciation of his obligations as a man. . .

886
01:35:26,920 --> 01:35:28,720
. . .and as a soldier.

887
01:35:30,520 --> 01:35:32,720
lf one can shame a coward. . .

888
01:35:34,520 --> 01:35:38,720
. . .I felt one might help him to regain his self-respect.

889
01:35:41,220 --> 01:35:42,820
This was on my mind.

890
01:35:45,320 --> 01:35:47,720
Now, I freely admit. . .

891
01:35:48,120 --> 01:35:50,120
. . .that my method was wrong. . .

892
01:35:51,120 --> 01:35:53,320
. . .but I hope you understand my motive. . .

893
01:35:54,720 --> 01:35:56,720
. . .and will accept this. . .

894
01:35:57,520 --> 01:35:59,120
. . .explanation. . .

895
01:36:00,720 --> 01:36:02,320
. . .and this. . .

896
01:36:04,320 --> 01:36:05,520
. . .apology.

897
01:36:07,720 --> 01:36:11,120
-Dismissed. -Ten-hut!

898
01:36:17,120 --> 01:36:20,720
Good evening, general. I want to report on a private poll I'm taking.

899
01:36:21,720 --> 01:36:22,720
What poll?

900
01:36:22,920 --> 01:36:24,120
The fan mail.

901
01:36:24,320 --> 01:36:26,920
Eleven percent con, 89 percent pro.

902
01:36:27,320 --> 01:36:31,720
And that 11 % of protest, in most cases, is both obscene and anonymous.

903
01:36:31,920 --> 01:36:35,520
But the pro letters are mostly from relatives and servicemen.

904
01:36:35,920 --> 01:36:39,320
"I want you to know we're proud our son is serving in your army.

905
01:36:39,720 --> 01:36:43,320
From the newspaper, we're not clear exactly what you did and why. . .

906
01:36:43,920 --> 01:36:46,120
. . .but we want you to know we're for you.

907
01:36:46,320 --> 01:36:48,120
Keep going, and God bless you. "

908
01:36:49,120 --> 01:36:50,720
Keep going, huh?

909
01:36:51,120 --> 01:36:52,520
Where?

910
01:36:56,120 --> 01:37:00,320
I thought you might like a sip of wine, general. It's New Year's.

911
01:37:00,520 --> 01:37:02,520
You didn't celebrate at all last night.

912
01:37:10,520 --> 01:37:12,720
I'm sick of sitting around this. . .

913
01:37:13,120 --> 01:37:15,320
. . .royal doghouse.

914
01:37:15,520 --> 01:37:18,320
We've taken Sicily. I'm ready for a new assignment.

915
01:37:19,320 --> 01:37:23,920
Maybe you've got it. Here's a radio message, just came in.

916
01:37:28,520 --> 01:37:29,720
Cod.

917
01:37:30,920 --> 01:37:32,120
I've been relieved.

918
01:37:34,720 --> 01:37:37,520
They've relieved me from command of the 7th Army.

919
01:37:38,520 --> 01:37:40,320
I don't believe it.

920
01:37:43,320 --> 01:37:44,320
Happy New Year.

921
01:37:50,920 --> 01:37:52,520
Just a minute, sir.

922
01:37:53,520 --> 01:37:56,120
Since they're sure to give you another command. . .

923
01:37:56,320 --> 01:37:59,720
. . .isn't it logical they'd relieve you here first?

924
01:38:00,920 --> 01:38:04,120
You mean command of all American troops going into Europe?

925
01:38:04,320 --> 01:38:07,720
It's possible. I know it's been discussed from time to time.

926
01:38:08,120 --> 01:38:12,520
The logic of it is so obvious, it couldn't mean anything else.

927
01:38:14,120 --> 01:38:18,520
Sir, I'm going to open this bottle of wine.

928
01:38:19,120 --> 01:38:20,520
No, Sir Cod. . .

929
01:38:20,720 --> 01:38:24,120
. . .but if you find a bottle of cognac, I'll help you drink it.

930
01:38:31,520 --> 01:38:35,320
-How you feeling tonight, general? -Not bad, not bad at all.

931
01:38:35,720 --> 01:38:38,520
-Get me some writing paper, will you? -Yes, sir.

932
01:38:39,320 --> 01:38:42,120
Your wife ever give you the devil for not writing?

933
01:38:42,320 --> 01:38:43,720
All the time, sir.

934
01:38:43,920 --> 01:38:47,720
Only I don't write as often as you do. Don't seem to get around to it.

935
01:38:49,320 --> 01:38:50,720
Lucky for us we got them.

936
01:38:51,720 --> 01:38:54,920
Who wants to marry a couple of broken-down old horse captains?

937
01:38:55,320 --> 01:38:57,920
That's what my wife says to me every time I come home, sir.

938
01:38:59,120 --> 01:39:00,920
Why are you up so late, George?

939
01:39:01,120 --> 01:39:03,720
Thought you'd like a nice hot bath or something.

940
01:39:11,920 --> 01:39:15,120
I got this sleeping pill from the doc, just in case you need it.

941
01:39:16,520 --> 01:39:18,120
Sleeping pill!

942
01:39:18,720 --> 01:39:21,720
-What's going on here? -I heard the news, sir.

943
01:39:22,120 --> 01:39:25,320
-They announced it on the radio. -What news?

944
01:39:26,120 --> 01:39:30,520
About General Bradley, sir. How they gave him the top American command.

945
01:39:32,520 --> 01:39:33,720
Oh.

946
01:39:35,120 --> 01:39:36,320
Oh, yeah.

947
01:39:38,720 --> 01:39:41,720
I just thought you might be feeling kind of low, sir.

948
01:39:58,920 --> 01:40:01,920
Your writing things, sir. Here on the desk, sir.

949
01:40:02,520 --> 01:40:05,120
Yeah. Thank you, George.

950
01:40:07,720 --> 01:40:09,120
One little dog face.

951
01:40:09,320 --> 01:40:12,520
One measly little slap. That's what done it.

952
01:40:15,520 --> 01:40:17,320
Ah, George.

953
01:40:19,520 --> 01:40:22,320
I wish I'd kissed the son of a bitch.

954
01:43:25,520 --> 01:43:28,320
(CLAPPING)

955
01:43:39,320 --> 01:43:44,120
(PATTON SPEAKS IN FRENCH)

956
01:43:51,520 --> 01:43:55,720
He's paying tribute to the Free French Forces under DeGaulle and Leclerc.

957
01:43:57,520 --> 01:44:00,120
(SPEAKS IN FRENCH)

958
01:44:11,920 --> 01:44:13,920
And to the people of the Resistance. . .

959
01:44:14,520 --> 01:44:17,520
. . .who risk their lives to help destroy the Germans.

960
01:44:24,720 --> 01:44:27,320
"France will be free again. I give you my word. "

961
01:44:54,720 --> 01:44:58,720
"Just as Free French troops liberated Corsica, Napoleon's place of birth. . .

962
01:44:59,120 --> 01:45:03,320
. . .I will someday land in France to liberate the birthplace of Lafayette. "

963
01:45:07,320 --> 01:45:10,520
General, the reporters would like a word with you.

964
01:45:13,720 --> 01:45:15,520
-Good afternoon. -General.

965
01:45:15,720 --> 01:45:18,720
Can you tell us the purpose of this visit to Corsica?

966
01:45:19,120 --> 01:45:20,720
General Eisenhower ordered me here.

967
01:45:21,120 --> 01:45:25,320
You wrote the mother of the boy you slapped, "The rat should've been shot. "

968
01:45:25,720 --> 01:45:27,920
-Is that true, general? -No comment.

969
01:45:28,320 --> 01:45:30,720
Sir, I understand Gen. Alexander suggested. . .

970
01:45:31,120 --> 01:45:33,920
. . .you take over Gen. Clark's Italian campaign. . .

971
01:45:34,120 --> 01:45:36,320
. . .but it was killed due to the incident.

972
01:45:36,720 --> 01:45:39,520
-No comment. -Can you say where you're going, sir?

973
01:45:39,920 --> 01:45:42,720
Off the record, Eisenhower's ordered me to Malta.

974
01:45:42,920 --> 01:45:44,120
Interview concluded.

975
01:45:44,520 --> 01:45:47,120
You plan on slapping any soldiers there, general?

976
01:46:03,135 --> 01:46:04,136
Malta?

977
01:46:04,345 --> 01:46:05,388
Yes, sir.

978
01:46:06,013 --> 01:46:08,140
Malta as a base...

979
01:46:09,642 --> 01:46:12,645
...then southern Greece. That is possible.

980
01:46:13,813 --> 01:46:15,689
Get me Field Marshal Keitel.

981
01:46:17,520 --> 01:46:20,720
PATTON: In 1 528, these forts were defended by. . .

982
01:46:21,120 --> 01:46:25,720
. . .400 Knights of Malta and 800 mercenaries. . .

983
01:46:26,320 --> 01:46:30,520
. . .against a force of 40,000 Turks.

984
01:46:31,320 --> 01:46:32,520
Codman.

985
01:46:35,320 --> 01:46:38,320
-Still no word from Gen. Eisenhower? -No, sir.

986
01:46:38,920 --> 01:46:42,320
Not even a response about the two turkeys I sent for Christmas?

987
01:46:42,720 --> 01:46:44,120
No, sir.

988
01:46:45,520 --> 01:46:48,920
Go ahead, gentlemen. Take a closer look for yourselves.

989
01:46:52,320 --> 01:46:56,520
Looks like you boys have hitched your wagon to a falling star.

990
01:46:57,520 --> 01:47:00,520
Pass the word. If anyone wants out, I'll understand.

991
01:47:00,720 --> 01:47:04,320
Sir, I can speak for the entire staff.

992
01:47:05,120 --> 01:47:09,120
We want to stay with you, no matter what duty you're assigned to.

993
01:47:12,920 --> 01:47:15,920
Up in London, they're planning the invasion of Europe.

994
01:47:18,320 --> 01:47:20,920
I've trained my mind, body and spirit for that.

995
01:47:21,120 --> 01:47:23,520
What, in God's name, am I doing here?

996
01:47:25,920 --> 01:47:27,320
All right.

997
01:47:27,720 --> 01:47:29,720
Let's get on to Cairo.

998
01:47:30,320 --> 01:47:32,720
See if the pyramids are still standing.

999
01:47:36,145 --> 01:47:39,148
There is only one reason for him to be in Cairo.

1000
01:47:39,440 --> 01:47:42,818
To confer with the Greek and Yugoslav governments in exile.

1001
01:47:43,194 --> 01:47:46,739
Let the Italians garrison Italy, it's their country.

1002
01:47:47,198 --> 01:47:51,785
We'll need our German troops to reinforce Crete and the Greek coast...

1003
01:47:51,994 --> 01:47:54,246
...if Patton strikes from Egypt!

1004
01:48:01,629 --> 01:48:03,714
I have some new information, sir.

1005
01:48:04,298 --> 01:48:09,136
Patton is under severe criticism. He may even be court-martialed.

1006
01:48:09,762 --> 01:48:11,597
He slapped an enlisted man.

1007
01:48:11,722 --> 01:48:14,141
You believe their newspapers?

1008
01:48:15,142 --> 01:48:18,729
Would they sacrifice their best commander because he slapped a soldier?

1009
01:48:54,520 --> 01:48:57,720
-This place is for me? -Yes, sir. This way, sir.

1010
01:48:58,920 --> 01:49:01,920
Whoever found it has a genius for cloak and dagger.

1011
01:49:20,320 --> 01:49:21,920
Who picked this cathouse?

1012
01:49:22,120 --> 01:49:23,920
I think it was Gen. Smith, sir.

1013
01:49:24,120 --> 01:49:26,120
To spite me, that son of a bitch.

1014
01:49:26,320 --> 01:49:29,920
-Welcome to London, Georgie. -Bedell. How are you?

1015
01:49:30,320 --> 01:49:32,520
-Is Ike here? -He asked me to brief you.

1016
01:49:32,720 --> 01:49:34,520
Would you excuse us, please?

1017
01:49:36,920 --> 01:49:38,920
Let me put you straight about Ike.

1018
01:49:39,320 --> 01:49:42,520
We hear a lot about you criticizing his decisions.

1019
01:49:42,720 --> 01:49:45,720
Not really. You know me. I'm just an old fool.

1020
01:49:46,320 --> 01:49:49,320
At times, I do wonder whether he isn't a limey at heart.

1021
01:49:49,520 --> 01:49:53,120
George, this is the toughest coalition ever attempted in history.

1022
01:49:53,520 --> 01:49:57,520
Ike's trying to hold it together and lick the Germans at the same time.

1023
01:49:57,920 --> 01:49:59,920
-It's a hell of a job. -I understand.

1024
01:50:00,520 --> 01:50:04,320
You have an important assignment connected to the Normandy invasion.

1025
01:50:04,720 --> 01:50:08,720
Good. I've studied the Overlord Plan and there's a number of flaws in it.

1026
01:50:09,120 --> 01:50:13,520
You can't depend on Monty taking Cannes by D-day. He'll never make it.

1027
01:50:14,320 --> 01:50:17,120
I've drawn up an alternate plan to land at Calais. . .

1028
01:50:17,520 --> 01:50:21,720
-. . .following an air bombardment-- -Will you just listen for a change?

1029
01:50:22,120 --> 01:50:24,720
Ike stood by you when everyone, I mean everyone. . .

1030
01:50:25,120 --> 01:50:27,520
. . .wanted Patton with a rope around his neck.

1031
01:50:33,320 --> 01:50:36,920
We're gonna let it leak out that you are here undercover.

1032
01:50:37,320 --> 01:50:40,320
That you're preparing to invade at the Pas de Calais.

1033
01:50:40,720 --> 01:50:43,120
We hope to pin down the German 1 5th Army there. . .

1034
01:50:43,520 --> 01:50:46,320
. . .so that they can't be used against us at Normandy.

1035
01:50:46,920 --> 01:50:48,720
Is that all I'm good for?

1036
01:50:48,720 --> 01:50:52,920
We're going to build an army of 1 2 divisions around you.

1037
01:50:53,120 --> 01:50:55,120
All fictitious, of course.

1038
01:50:55,520 --> 01:50:58,320
Dummy troop concentrations, dummy landing craft. . .

1039
01:50:58,520 --> 01:51:00,720
. . .simulated radio traffic.

1040
01:51:01,120 --> 01:51:05,520
The Germans are convinced that you will lead the main invasion effort.

1041
01:51:06,120 --> 01:51:07,920
Their agents will spot you soon. . .

1042
01:51:08,120 --> 01:51:10,720
. . .then we can move you to Knutsford.

1043
01:51:10,920 --> 01:51:14,120
-What do I do there? -Nothing. Absolutely nothing.

1044
01:51:15,720 --> 01:51:18,520
Frankly, George, you're on probation.

1045
01:51:18,920 --> 01:51:20,920
Take my advice and behave yourself.

1046
01:51:21,120 --> 01:51:22,520
Remember. . .

1047
01:51:22,920 --> 01:51:25,920
. . .your worst enemy is your own big mouth.

1048
01:51:44,620 --> 01:51:47,620
(BAND PLAYS)

1049
01:52:20,620 --> 01:52:24,020
Look at this nasty-faced son of a bitch. Ready for combat.

1050
01:52:24,220 --> 01:52:26,820
I'll call him William as in "the Conqueror. "

1051
01:52:27,320 --> 01:52:31,020
-Sir, should we leave him in the car? -No. Good afternoon, ladies.

1052
01:52:31,520 --> 01:52:33,120
Good afternoon.

1053
01:52:33,420 --> 01:52:36,720
(WlLLlE BARKS)

1054
01:52:38,020 --> 01:52:39,620
Watch this, Cod.

1055
01:52:39,920 --> 01:52:42,320
-Sir, he'll kill that dog. -I'll hold him.

1056
01:52:51,920 --> 01:52:55,620
I'm terribly sorry, general. Did Abigail frighten your dog?

1057
01:52:57,220 --> 01:52:59,020
That's quite all right, madam.

1058
01:52:59,920 --> 01:53:01,320
This way, sir.

1059
01:53:03,520 --> 01:53:05,020
Your name isn't William.

1060
01:53:06,120 --> 01:53:07,520
It's Willie.

1061
01:53:10,520 --> 01:53:12,020
WOMAN: My dear friends.

1062
01:53:12,420 --> 01:53:16,520
General George S. Patton, Jr., has accepted our invitation. . .

1063
01:53:16,920 --> 01:53:18,420
. . .to say a few words to you. . .

1064
01:53:18,720 --> 01:53:21,420
. . .on the occasion of this inaugural ceremony.

1065
01:53:27,220 --> 01:53:30,720
General Patton is not here in an official capacity. . .

1066
01:53:31,220 --> 01:53:33,620
. . .and I have assured him most earnestly. . .

1067
01:53:33,920 --> 01:53:36,320
. . .that nothing he says will be quoted.

1068
01:53:39,720 --> 01:53:42,720
May I present General Patton.

1069
01:53:54,120 --> 01:53:56,420
-Remember, sir, watch your language. -Yeah.

1070
01:53:57,120 --> 01:53:58,720
My dear ladies.

1071
01:53:59,420 --> 01:54:01,220
Until today. . .

1072
01:54:01,420 --> 01:54:06,320
. . .my only experience at welcoming has been. . .

1073
01:54:06,920 --> 01:54:11,820
. . .to welcome Germans and Italians to the infernal region.

1074
01:54:13,520 --> 01:54:15,920
At this I have been quite successful. . .

1075
01:54:16,320 --> 01:54:19,420
. . .since the troops, which I have had the honor to command. . .

1076
01:54:19,720 --> 01:54:22,220
. . .have, to date, killed or captured. . .

1077
01:54:22,520 --> 01:54:25,920
. . .some 1 70,000 of our enemies.

1078
01:54:34,920 --> 01:54:39,820
I feel that such clubs as these are of very real value. . .

1079
01:54:40,320 --> 01:54:43,020
. . .because I believe with Mr. Bernard Shaw. . .

1080
01:54:43,420 --> 01:54:47,020
. . .that the British and the Americans are two peoples. . .

1081
01:54:47,320 --> 01:54:50,920
. . .separated by a common language.

1082
01:54:53,720 --> 01:54:58,620
Since it is the destiny of the British and Americans to rule the world. . .

1083
01:55:00,420 --> 01:55:02,320
. . .the better we know each other. . .

1084
01:55:02,620 --> 01:55:04,420
. . .the better we will do it.

1085
01:55:05,720 --> 01:55:08,120
The Russians, don't forget the Russians.

1086
01:55:08,620 --> 01:55:10,220
I think that a club like this. . .

1087
01:55:10,620 --> 01:55:13,920
. . .is an ideal place for promoting mutual understanding.

1088
01:55:14,920 --> 01:55:20,120
Because as soon as our soldiers meet and get to know the English ladies. . .

1089
01:55:20,620 --> 01:55:25,820
. . .and write home and tell our women just how lovely you truly are. . .

1090
01:55:30,720 --> 01:55:33,520
. . .then the sooner the American ladies will get jealous. . .

1091
01:55:34,020 --> 01:55:36,820
. . .and force this war to a quick termination.

1092
01:55:41,020 --> 01:55:45,720
And then I'll get the chance to go to the Pacific and kill Japanese.

1093
01:56:04,520 --> 01:56:05,820
NARRATOR: All over the nation...

1094
01:56:06,120 --> 01:56:09,920
...mass meetings are held to protest General Patton 's statement...

1095
01:56:10,420 --> 01:56:13,120
... that Britain and America will rule the post war world.

1096
01:56:13,420 --> 01:56:15,220
That Russia will have no say.

1097
01:56:15,620 --> 01:56:19,720
Congressional leaders like Senator Clayburn Foss are quick to react.

1098
01:56:20,120 --> 01:56:22,720
This man has insulted our Russian allies...

1099
01:56:23,020 --> 01:56:25,820
...implying Anglo-American world rule.

1100
01:56:26,120 --> 01:56:29,120
In my opinion, he should be severely disciplined.

1101
01:56:29,620 --> 01:56:31,520
This time I didn't do a damn thing.

1102
01:56:31,920 --> 01:56:34,420
They promised there wouldn't be any reporters.

1103
01:56:34,720 --> 01:56:36,920
I made a few remarks off the record.

1104
01:56:37,220 --> 01:56:39,620
Ike told you to keep your mouth shut.

1105
01:56:39,920 --> 01:56:43,520
You know how suspicious the Russians are of the British and us.

1106
01:56:43,920 --> 01:56:47,120
I was only trying to be polite to the old ladies.

1107
01:56:47,420 --> 01:56:52,620
lf I'd seen the Russians there, I'd have mentioned the sons of bitches.

1108
01:56:53,320 --> 01:56:56,120
Bedell, I don't know anything about politics.

1109
01:56:56,520 --> 01:56:58,320
I have no political ambitions.

1110
01:56:58,620 --> 01:57:01,520
All I want to do is to command an army in combat.

1111
01:57:01,820 --> 01:57:03,820
Well, it's out of our hands now.

1112
01:57:04,120 --> 01:57:07,320
Ike sent a message last night to the chief of staff.

1113
01:57:07,720 --> 01:57:12,720
Now it's up to General Marshall whether you stay here as a decoy. . .

1114
01:57:13,120 --> 01:57:15,120
. . .or he sends you home.

1115
01:57:17,720 --> 01:57:19,320
He's a good man.

1116
01:57:19,920 --> 01:57:22,020
At least he's a fair man.

1117
01:57:22,520 --> 01:57:24,320
I'll let it sit with him.

1118
01:57:39,420 --> 01:57:40,820
PATTON: George. . .

1119
01:57:42,120 --> 01:57:44,320
. . .our war is over.

1120
01:57:44,620 --> 01:57:45,820
Over, sir?

1121
01:57:46,520 --> 01:57:49,720
It's just a question of waiting for the orders now.

1122
01:57:57,320 --> 01:57:59,120
I feel I'm. . . .

1123
01:58:00,920 --> 01:58:05,120
I'm destined to achieve some great thing. What, I don't know.

1124
01:58:06,920 --> 01:58:10,920
But this last incident is. . .

1125
01:58:11,820 --> 01:58:15,720
. . .so trivial in its nature and so terrible in its effect--

1126
01:58:16,420 --> 01:58:19,920
It can't be an accident. It has to be the work of God.

1127
01:58:21,020 --> 01:58:22,320
Yes, sir.

1128
01:58:23,020 --> 01:58:25,420
The last great opportunity of a lifetime. . .

1129
01:58:25,720 --> 01:58:30,120
. . .an entire world at war and I'm left out of it?

1130
01:58:30,520 --> 01:58:31,820
No, sir.

1131
01:58:32,220 --> 01:58:34,220
God will not permit this to happen!

1132
01:58:34,720 --> 01:58:39,120
I am going to be allowed to fulfil my destiny!

1133
01:58:44,220 --> 01:58:46,120
His will be done.

1134
01:58:58,820 --> 01:59:02,120
NARRATOR: In the greatest amphibious operation ever attempted...

1135
01:59:02,420 --> 01:59:05,020
...a predawn naval bombardment prepares the way...

1136
01:59:05,320 --> 01:59:08,320
...for allied soldiers to assault the Normandy beaches...

1137
01:59:08,720 --> 01:59:12,120
...and claw out a desperate foothold on the continent of Europe.

1138
01:59:27,420 --> 01:59:32,520
I knew Montgomery couldn't take Caen on D-day or D-plus-1 0. And I said so.

1139
01:59:32,920 --> 01:59:36,720
And here they are all hung up in the hedgerow country.

1140
01:59:37,120 --> 01:59:41,120
They should pivot the way von Schlieffen planned it in World War I.

1141
01:59:42,120 --> 01:59:45,720
Then we might get a chance to do some real broken field running.

1142
01:59:46,820 --> 01:59:48,720
But they don't listen to me.

1143
01:59:51,920 --> 01:59:54,320
What a way to enter the continent of Europe.

1144
01:59:54,620 --> 01:59:57,020
Along with all the rest of the spare parts.

1145
01:59:57,720 --> 02:00:00,320
Sir, everything on this plane is high priority.

1146
02:00:01,520 --> 02:00:05,220
Gen. Bradley wouldn't send for you unless he had something in mind.

1147
02:00:05,520 --> 02:00:09,020
I'll tell you, Cod. I've learned my lesson.

1148
02:00:09,820 --> 02:00:13,220
lf I ever do get another chance, I'm gonna keep my mouth shut.

1149
02:00:15,120 --> 02:00:17,020
I'm gonna play the game.

1150
02:00:17,520 --> 02:00:19,520
lf I forget, you remind me.

1151
02:00:20,320 --> 02:00:24,520
-I'll give a gentle nudge in the ribs. -Give me a swift kick in the ass.

1152
02:00:25,520 --> 02:00:26,820
Yes, sir.

1153
02:00:48,620 --> 02:00:50,120
Welcome to France, sir.

1154
02:00:50,420 --> 02:00:52,720
Hope the war's still on. Where's the boss?

1155
02:00:53,020 --> 02:00:54,220
Right this way, sir.

1156
02:01:31,420 --> 02:01:34,920
Patton, haven't seen you since Messina.

1157
02:01:35,320 --> 02:01:36,320
How are you?

1158
02:01:36,520 --> 02:01:39,120
You're doing a splendid job decoying the Jerries.

1159
02:01:39,420 --> 02:01:41,820
You'll forgive me, I'm off to the front.

1160
02:01:42,120 --> 02:01:43,920
Best of everything, old boy.

1161
02:01:48,120 --> 02:01:49,620
By the way. . .

1162
02:01:50,120 --> 02:01:53,420
. . .intelligence confirms that I'm against Rommel again.

1163
02:01:58,220 --> 02:01:59,620
Rommel.

1164
02:02:01,520 --> 02:02:02,920
Hi, how are you, George?

1165
02:02:03,920 --> 02:02:07,220
-Pretty fair, Brad. How are you? -Fine.

1166
02:02:11,120 --> 02:02:13,320
Well. My, my.

1167
02:02:13,720 --> 02:02:15,320
Isn't this plush?

1168
02:02:15,520 --> 02:02:18,420
Looks like you're bucking for archbishop.

1169
02:02:18,820 --> 02:02:21,920
Chet Hansen had this rig built for me. George, sit down.

1170
02:02:22,620 --> 02:02:26,420
Ike wanted me to talk to you since we can level with each other.

1171
02:02:26,820 --> 02:02:28,020
That's right.

1172
02:02:28,920 --> 02:02:32,720
We're making 3rd Army operational when I take over 12th Army group.

1173
02:02:33,120 --> 02:02:34,520
Do I get it?

1174
02:02:35,120 --> 02:02:36,620
I'll be honest with you.

1175
02:02:37,020 --> 02:02:38,620
I've had reservations.

1176
02:02:39,520 --> 02:02:42,520
You've been my senior ever since I left the academy.

1177
02:02:42,920 --> 02:02:46,720
You were the boss in North Africa and Sicily and I just thought. . .

1178
02:02:48,120 --> 02:02:50,220
. . .well, it might be a problem for us.

1179
02:02:50,820 --> 02:02:52,420
It wouldn't bother me.

1180
02:02:52,720 --> 02:02:54,620
There's one other thing.

1181
02:02:54,920 --> 02:02:56,820
We're different kinds of people.

1182
02:02:57,020 --> 02:02:59,820
Goddamn it, Brad, you're always right.

1183
02:03:00,120 --> 02:03:04,520
With your brains and my screwy ideas, we make a great team, like in Sicily.

1184
02:03:05,020 --> 02:03:09,120
Truthfully, if I had been your senior in Sicily, I would have relieved you.

1185
02:03:11,920 --> 02:03:13,120
Brad. . .

1186
02:03:14,820 --> 02:03:17,420
. . .I'm not crawling on my belly to get a command.

1187
02:03:17,720 --> 02:03:20,320
For God's sake, get me in this fight.

1188
02:03:22,020 --> 02:03:25,320
The only way out of the doghouse is to do something great.

1189
02:03:25,620 --> 02:03:27,220
I gotta get back in the war!

1190
02:03:27,520 --> 02:03:30,620
Hitler's own people tried to kill him a few days ago.

1191
02:03:31,020 --> 02:03:33,320
First thing you know, it'll be over and. . . .

1192
02:03:36,720 --> 02:03:37,820
I'll. . .

1193
02:03:40,220 --> 02:03:43,020
. . .keep my mouth shut. I'll behave myself.

1194
02:03:46,020 --> 02:03:47,720
I give you my word.

1195
02:03:51,520 --> 02:03:52,920
George. . .

1196
02:03:53,620 --> 02:03:56,120
. . .I've been working on a plan called Cobra.

1197
02:03:56,820 --> 02:03:58,420
I'd like your opinion.

1198
02:03:58,720 --> 02:04:01,020
We've been slugging through hedgerow country. . .

1199
02:04:01,320 --> 02:04:04,420
. . .half an acre a day and we've got to find a way out.

1200
02:04:04,820 --> 02:04:06,320
I want to use this road.

1201
02:04:06,520 --> 02:04:08,220
The Saint L?Periers road.

1202
02:04:08,520 --> 02:04:11,120
Monty will pin down the enemy forces at Caen.

1203
02:04:11,420 --> 02:04:14,920
We'll pulverize an area 3 1 /2 miles wide with bombing.

1204
02:04:15,320 --> 02:04:17,320
Then seven divisions will follow.

1205
02:04:17,620 --> 02:04:22,520
The 3rd Army will swing around here, a sweeping end run right across France.

1206
02:04:23,420 --> 02:04:24,720
What do you think?

1207
02:04:26,120 --> 02:04:31,320
I think you'll need a screwball old cavalryman to command the 3rd Army.

1208
02:04:32,620 --> 02:04:34,220
George. . .

1209
02:04:36,420 --> 02:04:40,920
. . .Ike came to that conclusion in London three months ago.

1210
02:04:41,720 --> 02:04:42,920
He what?

1211
02:04:43,920 --> 02:04:47,920
Why, that dirty--! I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

1212
02:04:48,320 --> 02:04:50,220
I promise to keep my mouth shut.

1213
02:04:51,420 --> 02:04:54,620
(SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

1214
02:04:55,475 --> 02:04:56,893
What's this activity near Coutances?

1215
02:04:57,477 --> 02:05:00,939
Enemy armored forces driving through our defenses at Lessay.

1216
02:05:01,022 --> 02:05:06,361
"American tanks moving rapidly, slicing through to the rear areas".

1217
02:05:06,986 --> 02:05:09,781
This sounds like Patton, Field Marshal.

1218
02:05:10,114 --> 02:05:11,282
Patton is in England.

1219
02:05:11,824 --> 02:05:13,034
Do we know this?

1220
02:05:13,785 --> 02:05:17,622
The landing in Normandy is merely a diversionary maneuver.

1221
02:05:18,540 --> 02:05:21,918
The real invasion will come at Calais and Patton will lead it.

1222
02:05:22,210 --> 02:05:26,881
The F¨¹hrer says that the Fifteenth Army is not to be moved to Normandy.

1223
02:05:27,090 --> 02:05:30,176
Those men are sitting on the beach at Calais throwing pebbles at each other...

1224
02:05:30,385 --> 02:05:33,930
...while our men are being slaughtered in Normandy.

1225
02:05:34,180 --> 02:05:38,476
The Fifteenth Army is waiting for Patton at Calais and he will land there.

1226
02:05:41,020 --> 02:05:44,941
You seem perfectly willing to accept this nonsense, Jodl.

1227
02:05:46,025 --> 02:05:47,026
Why?

1228
02:05:50,071 --> 02:05:53,324
Because I am not prepared to dispute the F¨¹hrer.

1229
02:06:47,020 --> 02:06:50,020
George could have the courtesy to tell us where he's going.

1230
02:07:03,220 --> 02:07:06,620
Good God, look at that. Where you going, general?

1231
02:07:07,020 --> 02:07:08,120
Berlin.

1232
02:07:08,420 --> 02:07:12,220
I'm going to personally shoot that paper-hanging son of a bitch.

1233
02:07:12,520 --> 02:07:15,320
(CHEERING)

1234
02:07:53,620 --> 02:07:57,020
Hold it. Hold it!

1235
02:07:58,220 --> 02:07:59,520
This place isn't on the map.

1236
02:07:59,920 --> 02:08:02,620
You know why? We've run clear off the map.

1237
02:08:14,520 --> 02:08:16,920
Give George a headline, and he's good for another 30 miles.

1238
02:08:50,920 --> 02:08:53,220
(HONKING)

1239
02:09:16,520 --> 02:09:18,520
SOLDIER: Atten-hut!

1240
02:09:19,520 --> 02:09:20,820
Hold it!

1241
02:09:25,020 --> 02:09:28,620
Pay attention. We're gonna clean this mess up right now.

1242
02:09:29,020 --> 02:09:32,520
Let's move this vehicle out this way. This one out this way.

1243
02:09:33,020 --> 02:09:35,720
Back that thing up there, and we'll take this one here.

1244
02:09:36,120 --> 02:09:38,420
All right, get up off your ass. Let's go now!

1245
02:09:50,320 --> 02:09:52,120
That's it. That's the way to move.

1246
02:09:52,420 --> 02:09:55,220
Good boy. All right, come on.

1247
02:09:55,520 --> 02:09:58,620
Come on, now. Here we go. Come on. That's it!

1248
02:09:58,920 --> 02:10:00,720
That's it! Gun it!

1249
02:10:01,420 --> 02:10:03,220
Gun that thing!

1250
02:10:03,620 --> 02:10:05,420
Okay, come on.

1251
02:10:07,120 --> 02:10:08,320
Watch it!

1252
02:10:09,120 --> 02:10:11,420
Go, go, go! Come on. Hold it up.

1253
02:10:11,820 --> 02:10:13,920
Come on, baby. Yeah, yeah. Come on.

1254
02:10:15,120 --> 02:10:16,720
That's it.

1255
02:10:17,320 --> 02:10:18,820
Come on, now.

1256
02:10:21,420 --> 02:10:23,320
-Chet. -Yeah, will do.

1257
02:10:26,320 --> 02:10:29,820
Come on, keep coming. Keep coming. Hold it up there.

1258
02:10:32,820 --> 02:10:34,220
Now come on! Hold it!

1259
02:10:34,520 --> 02:10:37,620
Hey, dummy, hold the fricking tank!

1260
02:10:43,120 --> 02:10:44,520
That's it. Come on.

1261
02:10:44,720 --> 02:10:46,020
Good boy.

1262
02:10:48,920 --> 02:10:50,520
-Hold it up there. -General!

1263
02:10:50,820 --> 02:10:53,020
General Bradley wants to have a word with you.

1264
02:10:53,420 --> 02:10:56,120
Okay. Come on!

1265
02:10:57,520 --> 02:11:01,720
Okay. Hold it up. Take over.

1266
02:11:09,420 --> 02:11:12,020
George, you'd make a good traffic cop.

1267
02:11:13,720 --> 02:11:16,220
George this drive has been magnificent. . .

1268
02:11:16,720 --> 02:11:19,420
. . .but I'm sorry to say I have to slow you down.

1269
02:11:19,720 --> 02:11:23,720
-What the hell for? -We'll have to cut off your supplies.

1270
02:11:24,220 --> 02:11:27,820
Gasoline, ammunition, everything. We're up against new priorities.

1271
02:11:28,220 --> 02:11:31,620
-I think I smell Montgomery. -Take it easy, George.

1272
02:11:32,120 --> 02:11:34,920
There are serious issues involved. Political issues.

1273
02:11:35,320 --> 02:11:37,020
By God, it is Montgomery.

1274
02:11:37,420 --> 02:11:41,220
The launching sites for the B-2 bombs are all in his area.

1275
02:11:41,620 --> 02:11:43,520
Churchill wants those bases destroyed.

1276
02:11:44,120 --> 02:11:47,120
Hitler kills more civilians in London than soldiers.

1277
02:11:47,520 --> 02:11:49,120
Expect Montgomery to do anything?

1278
02:11:49,920 --> 02:11:53,520
You give me gasoline and I'll gain ground with it, kill Germans too.

1279
02:11:53,920 --> 02:11:55,720
Give me 400,000 gallons. I'll go to Berlin.

1280
02:11:56,120 --> 02:11:57,720
George, I can't do it.

1281
02:11:58,020 --> 02:11:59,820
The Siegfried line is an empty shell.

1282
02:12:00,120 --> 02:12:02,220
They stripped the equipment and sent it east.

1283
02:12:02,620 --> 02:12:05,220
It's crawling with cows. I can punch through in two days.

1284
02:12:05,620 --> 02:12:08,520
There's no use in arguing with me. It wasn't my idea.

1285
02:12:08,820 --> 02:12:10,720
Why did you pick me to command?

1286
02:12:11,120 --> 02:12:13,020
I didn't pick you.

1287
02:12:15,020 --> 02:12:16,420
Ike picked you.

1288
02:12:19,920 --> 02:12:22,320
George, you have performed brilliantly.

1289
02:12:22,720 --> 02:12:24,420
You are loyal, dedicated.

1290
02:12:24,720 --> 02:12:27,420
You're one of the best I've got, but you don't know when to shut up.

1291
02:12:27,820 --> 02:12:31,320
George, you're a pain in the neck.

1292
02:12:35,220 --> 02:12:37,420
I have a lot of faults, Brad.

1293
02:12:37,720 --> 02:12:40,020
But ingratitude isn't one of them.

1294
02:12:40,420 --> 02:12:41,820
I owe you a lot.

1295
02:12:42,920 --> 02:12:46,520
Hell, I know I'm a prima donna. I admit it.

1296
02:12:46,920 --> 02:12:50,020
What I can't stand about Monty is, he won't admit it.

1297
02:13:02,420 --> 02:13:04,620
(TANK SPUTTERS)

1298
02:13:15,620 --> 02:13:18,720
Captain, the Bailey's run out of gas.

1299
02:13:19,320 --> 02:13:21,020
The point tank has run out too.

1300
02:13:22,720 --> 02:13:24,920
And there's a kraut column up ahead.

1301
02:13:25,420 --> 02:13:26,820
Yeah, I know.

1302
02:15:29,120 --> 02:15:30,920
PATTON: Were you in command here, captain?

1303
02:15:32,620 --> 02:15:33,620
I was in command.

1304
02:15:34,720 --> 02:15:38,320
My tank platoon was supporting an infantry company.

1305
02:15:38,720 --> 02:15:43,320
Tanks ran out of gas, so we had to fight it out.

1306
02:15:45,120 --> 02:15:47,620
We started 1 1 :00 last night.

1307
02:15:49,220 --> 02:15:51,220
Finished a couple hours ago.

1308
02:15:53,420 --> 02:15:57,720
This morning the fighting was hand-to-hand.

1309
02:16:46,320 --> 02:16:48,120
I had a dream last night.

1310
02:16:50,420 --> 02:16:53,520
In my dream it came to me. . .

1311
02:16:53,820 --> 02:16:57,020
. . .that right now the whole Nazi Reich is mine for the taking.

1312
02:16:57,420 --> 02:17:01,620
Think about that, Cod. I was nearly sent home in disgrace.

1313
02:17:02,520 --> 02:17:05,020
Now I have precisely the right instrument. . .

1314
02:17:05,320 --> 02:17:09,920
. . .at precisely the right moment of history and exactly the right place.

1315
02:17:10,420 --> 02:17:11,720
The Saar?

1316
02:17:12,020 --> 02:17:14,020
This will change too, very quickly.

1317
02:17:14,320 --> 02:17:16,820
Like a planet spinning off into the universe.

1318
02:17:17,220 --> 02:17:19,920
A moment like this won't come again for 1 000 years.

1319
02:17:20,220 --> 02:17:22,920
All I need is a few miserable gallons of gasoline.

1320
02:17:23,520 --> 02:17:26,920
Right now, the weak spot is here.

1321
02:17:28,620 --> 02:17:31,920
In 1 0 days, we could be in Berlin.

1322
02:17:32,320 --> 02:17:35,620
What about the fortifications that were done in Metz?

1323
02:17:37,720 --> 02:17:39,820
Fixed fortifications, huh?

1324
02:17:40,120 --> 02:17:43,020
Monuments to the stupidity of man.

1325
02:17:43,920 --> 02:17:47,220
When mountain ranges and oceans could be overcome. . .

1326
02:17:47,720 --> 02:17:49,620
. . .anything built by man can be overcome.

1327
02:17:54,420 --> 02:17:57,020
You know how I'm sure they're finished out there?

1328
02:17:59,320 --> 02:18:00,620
The carts.

1329
02:18:02,420 --> 02:18:05,520
They're using carts to move their wounded and the supplies.

1330
02:18:07,520 --> 02:18:11,320
The carts came to me in my dream. I couldn't figure it out.

1331
02:18:12,820 --> 02:18:14,520
Then I remembered. . .

1332
02:18:16,520 --> 02:18:20,720
. . .that nightmare in the snow. The agonizing retreat from Moscow.

1333
02:18:21,820 --> 02:18:23,520
How cold it was.

1334
02:18:27,020 --> 02:18:30,520
They threw the wounded and what was left of the supplies in the carts.

1335
02:18:31,820 --> 02:18:33,620
Napoleon was finished.

1336
02:18:36,020 --> 02:18:38,620
Not any color left. Not even the red of blood.

1337
02:18:40,020 --> 02:18:41,620
Only the snow.

1338
02:18:46,720 --> 02:18:48,020
Look at this, Cod.

1339
02:18:55,820 --> 02:18:57,220
I love it.

1340
02:19:01,320 --> 02:19:03,420
God help me, I do love it so.

1341
02:19:07,620 --> 02:19:09,220
I love it more than my life.

1342
02:19:18,420 --> 02:19:21,520
NARRATOR: Paris is liberated, and French troops lead the way.

1343
02:19:22,520 --> 02:19:27,020
The Allies march into the city after four years of Nazi occupation.

1344
02:19:27,620 --> 02:19:30,320
The hard-fighting French 2nd Armored Division...

1345
02:19:30,720 --> 02:19:33,020
...under Major General Jacques Leclerc...

1346
02:19:33,320 --> 02:19:35,020
...gets an unforgettable welcome...

1347
02:19:35,620 --> 02:19:37,620
...as they enter their beloved Paris.

1348
02:19:42,820 --> 02:19:44,620
In a powerful drive to the north...

1349
02:19:44,820 --> 02:19:48,220
... General Montgomery cuts off and bypasses the French coastal towns...

1350
02:19:48,720 --> 02:19:51,020
...of Boulogne, Calais and Dunkirk.

1351
02:19:51,420 --> 02:19:54,420
Pushing on to capture the vital Belgian port of Antwerp.

1352
02:20:00,620 --> 02:20:02,320
Meanwhile, the main body of Patton 's army...

1353
02:20:02,620 --> 02:20:06,720
...resupplied now and rolling like a juggernaut, slashes toward the Saar.

1354
02:20:07,920 --> 02:20:09,820
Nazi resistance appears to crumble.

1355
02:20:10,220 --> 02:20:14,720
It seems that nothing can stop our troops from driving on into Germany.

1356
02:20:23,720 --> 02:20:26,720
-Sir, General Bradley on your line. -Good, good.

1357
02:20:32,920 --> 02:20:35,520
Brad, listen, I've got a bridgehead across the Saar.

1358
02:20:36,020 --> 02:20:37,120
I'm on my way to Germany.

1359
02:20:37,320 --> 02:20:39,920
Wait a minute, George. There's a lot of trouble up north.

1360
02:20:40,220 --> 02:20:45,120
I want you to transfer tank armor to Middleton's 8th Corps right away.

1361
02:20:45,820 --> 02:20:47,320
Brad, you can't do that.

1362
02:20:47,620 --> 02:20:50,520
George, listen. I don't have time to argue.

1363
02:20:50,920 --> 02:20:53,620
There's a lot of enemy activity up around Ardennes.

1364
02:20:54,020 --> 02:20:56,220
No, I don't know how serious it is. . .

1365
02:20:56,520 --> 02:21:00,820
. . .but Ike wants us to meet with Bedell Smith tomorrow at Verdun.

1366
02:21:01,320 --> 02:21:02,420
Be there at 1 1 00.

1367
02:21:03,020 --> 02:21:04,320
Yes, sir.

1368
02:21:45,320 --> 02:21:48,020
PATTON: There's absolutely no reason for us to assume. . .

1369
02:21:48,420 --> 02:21:51,020
. . .that the Germans are mounting a major offense.

1370
02:21:52,420 --> 02:21:56,320
The weather is awful and their supplies are low.

1371
02:21:57,420 --> 02:22:00,920
The Germans haven't mounted a winter attack since Frederick the Great.

1372
02:22:03,820 --> 02:22:06,920
Therefore I believe that's exactly what they're going to do.

1373
02:22:48,920 --> 02:22:51,720
I want you to start making contingency plans. . .

1374
02:22:52,020 --> 02:22:53,720
. . .for pulling out of our eastward attack.

1375
02:22:54,120 --> 02:22:56,820
Changing directions 90 degrees, moving up to Luxembourg.

1376
02:22:58,820 --> 02:23:00,520
Don't look so stunned, gentlemen.

1377
02:23:01,320 --> 02:23:03,820
I want you to plan for three possible axes of attack.

1378
02:23:04,120 --> 02:23:05,920
From Diekirch, due north.

1379
02:23:06,320 --> 02:23:10,420
From Orléans to Bastogne.

1380
02:23:10,820 --> 02:23:14,220
From Neufchâteau against the German left flank.

1381
02:23:34,720 --> 02:23:36,920
We've identified four German armies:

1382
02:23:37,320 --> 02:23:42,120
The 7th, the 5th Panzer, 6th SS Panzer and the 1 5th.

1383
02:23:42,820 --> 02:23:44,720
They've hit us with 26 divisions.

1384
02:23:45,020 --> 02:23:47,820
They've overran two regimens of the 1 06th Division.

1385
02:23:48,120 --> 02:23:51,120
And 7500 of our men were forced to surrender.

1386
02:23:51,720 --> 02:23:54,120
Our concern is that von Rundstedt. . .

1387
02:23:54,420 --> 02:23:58,220
. . .has the 1 01 st Airborne trapped here at Bastogne.

1388
02:24:01,320 --> 02:24:05,320
Bastogne, by the way, is the key to this entire area.

1389
02:24:06,220 --> 02:24:09,920
lf we can hold it, we can break up the entire German offensive.

1390
02:24:10,720 --> 02:24:13,320
lf they take it, we're in serious trouble.

1391
02:24:14,520 --> 02:24:16,820
Ike wants to know if anybody can go. . .

1392
02:24:17,120 --> 02:24:20,220
. . .and relieve the 1 01 st before they're torn to pieces.

1393
02:24:22,520 --> 02:24:24,820
There's nothing Montgomery can do.

1394
02:24:25,120 --> 02:24:27,420
At any rate, not for some weeks.

1395
02:24:28,220 --> 02:24:30,120
What about you, George?

1396
02:24:31,120 --> 02:24:33,420
I can attack with three divisions in 48 hours.

1397
02:24:37,620 --> 02:24:39,120
I'd give myself some leeway.

1398
02:24:39,720 --> 02:24:41,820
Ike wants a realistic estimate, George.

1399
02:24:42,120 --> 02:24:46,120
You're in the middle of a fight now. It's over a hundred miles to Bastogne.

1400
02:24:46,620 --> 02:24:48,820
My staff's already working out the details.

1401
02:24:51,120 --> 02:24:54,020
Frankly, I don't see how it's possible.

1402
02:24:54,720 --> 02:24:56,620
Not in this kind of weather.

1403
02:24:57,320 --> 02:25:00,020
I should have thought you'd want to fall back and regroup.

1404
02:25:00,320 --> 02:25:03,020
Not me. I don't like to pay for the same real estate twice.

1405
02:25:03,320 --> 02:25:04,620
TEDDER: But what about your men?

1406
02:25:05,120 --> 02:25:09,120
You can't cart them off 1 00 miles, expecting them to attack without rest.

1407
02:25:09,820 --> 02:25:10,920
I trained these men.

1408
02:25:11,220 --> 02:25:13,020
They'll do what I tell them to do.

1409
02:25:13,320 --> 02:25:16,920
We hadn't realized you were so popular with your troops, general.

1410
02:25:18,420 --> 02:25:22,220
I'm not. They'll do it because they're good soldiers.

1411
02:25:22,520 --> 02:25:26,320
And because they realize, as I do, that we can still lose this war.

1412
02:25:29,720 --> 02:25:32,320
Then I think I can speak for Field Marshal Montgomery.

1413
02:25:33,420 --> 02:25:35,720
He'd say you're asking the impossible of your men.

1414
02:25:36,020 --> 02:25:37,620
Of course he would.

1415
02:25:37,920 --> 02:25:41,020
Cause he's never realized that's what we're in business for.

1416
02:26:32,720 --> 02:26:35,320
(BOMB EXPLODES)

1417
02:26:59,420 --> 02:27:01,820
General McAuliffe refused a German surrender demand.

1418
02:27:02,220 --> 02:27:03,720
You know what he said?

1419
02:27:04,920 --> 02:27:06,120
What?

1420
02:27:06,520 --> 02:27:08,120
He said, "Nuts. "

1421
02:27:10,320 --> 02:27:11,520
Keep them moving, colonel.

1422
02:27:11,820 --> 02:27:14,120
A man that eloquent has to be saved.

1423
02:27:57,120 --> 02:28:00,220
(SILENCE)

1424
02:29:32,420 --> 02:29:34,320
This is where it pays off.

1425
02:29:34,720 --> 02:29:36,320
The training and discipline.

1426
02:29:37,420 --> 02:29:39,520
No other outfit in the world.

1427
02:29:40,320 --> 02:29:43,820
Pulled out of a winter battle, move a hundred miles.

1428
02:29:44,320 --> 02:29:48,220
Going to a major attack with no rest, no sleep, no hot food.

1429
02:29:48,620 --> 02:29:52,120
God! God, I'm proud of these men!

1430
02:30:17,820 --> 02:30:21,820
Sir, von Rundstedt's thrown another panzer division against Bastogne.

1431
02:30:22,220 --> 02:30:24,320
101 st Airborne's barely holding on.

1432
02:30:24,620 --> 02:30:28,820
We need damned air cover. lf we had decent weather, we might make it.

1433
02:30:29,520 --> 02:30:31,420
CARVER: General Mason, sir.

1434
02:30:46,120 --> 02:30:49,120
Hello, Mase? Listen, we're short on foot soldiers.

1435
02:30:49,520 --> 02:30:53,020
Cannibalize your antiaircraft units and turn them into riflemen.

1436
02:30:53,420 --> 02:30:55,220
Yes, every last one you can find.

1437
02:30:55,620 --> 02:30:56,820
Good evening, general.

1438
02:30:57,020 --> 02:31:00,120
I just got the weather report for tomorrow. More snow.

1439
02:31:00,620 --> 02:31:02,420
There goes our air cover.

1440
02:31:02,820 --> 02:31:05,320
We may have to wait for better weather.

1441
02:31:05,720 --> 02:31:10,420
Brave men dying up there. I won't wait, not an hour, not a minute.

1442
02:31:12,920 --> 02:31:14,320
Going to keep moving.

1443
02:31:14,520 --> 02:31:16,220
ls that clear?

1444
02:31:18,420 --> 02:31:21,820
We're going to attack all night and attack tomorrow morning!

1445
02:31:23,020 --> 02:31:25,220
lf we're not victorious. . .

1446
02:31:27,620 --> 02:31:29,520
. . .let no one come back alive.

1447
02:31:41,420 --> 02:31:43,120
You know something, general?

1448
02:31:43,320 --> 02:31:47,420
Sometimes, they can't tell when you're acting and when you're not.

1449
02:31:49,420 --> 02:31:51,520
It isn't important for them to know.

1450
02:31:53,120 --> 02:31:55,220
It's only important for me to know.

1451
02:32:02,420 --> 02:32:05,620
-You want to see me, general? -Oh, yeah, chaplain.

1452
02:32:06,020 --> 02:32:08,520
I'm tired of 3rd Army having to fight Germans. . .

1453
02:32:08,920 --> 02:32:11,120
. . .with supreme command, no gasoline. . .

1454
02:32:11,420 --> 02:32:13,320
. . .and now this ungodly weather.

1455
02:32:13,720 --> 02:32:15,720
I want a prayer, a weather prayer.

1456
02:32:16,820 --> 02:32:18,120
A weather prayer, sir?

1457
02:32:18,420 --> 02:32:21,320
Yes, let's see if you can't get God working with us.

1458
02:32:21,720 --> 02:32:24,020
Gonna take a thick rug for that kind of praying.

1459
02:32:24,420 --> 02:32:26,520
I don't care if it takes a flying carpet.

1460
02:32:26,820 --> 02:32:29,620
I don't know how this will be received, general.

1461
02:32:30,120 --> 02:32:32,920
Praying for good weather so we can kill our fellow man.

1462
02:32:33,220 --> 02:32:36,220
I assure you, because of my relations with the Almighty. . .

1463
02:32:36,520 --> 02:32:39,620
. . .if you write a good prayer, we'll have good weather.

1464
02:32:40,120 --> 02:32:42,620
And I expect that prayer within an hour.

1465
02:32:43,420 --> 02:32:44,720
Yes, sir.

1466
02:33:15,520 --> 02:33:18,320
"Almighty and most merciful Father. . .

1467
02:33:19,320 --> 02:33:21,720
. . .we humbly beseech Thee. . .

1468
02:33:22,020 --> 02:33:24,120
. . .of Thy great goodness. . .

1469
02:33:25,220 --> 02:33:28,520
. . .to restrain this immoderate weather. . .

1470
02:33:29,920 --> 02:33:32,120
. . .with which we've had to contend.

1471
02:33:34,320 --> 02:33:37,020
Grant us fair weather for battle.

1472
02:33:38,320 --> 02:33:40,020
Graciously hearken to us...

1473
02:33:41,220 --> 02:33:43,320
...as soldiers who call upon Thee...

1474
02:33:43,920 --> 02:33:46,320
... that armed with Thy power...

1475
02:33:46,820 --> 02:33:49,620
... we may advance from victory to victory...

1476
02:33:50,020 --> 02:33:52,220
...and crush the oppression...

1477
02:33:52,620 --> 02:33:55,020
...and wickedness of our enemies...

1478
02:33:55,320 --> 02:33:57,520
...and establish Thy justice...

1479
02:33:58,420 --> 02:34:01,620
...among men and nations.

1480
02:34:05,220 --> 02:34:06,420
Amen. ''

1481
02:34:21,920 --> 02:34:23,220
Weather's perfect.

1482
02:34:24,620 --> 02:34:27,320
Cod, get me that chaplain.

1483
02:34:27,820 --> 02:34:30,620
He's in good with the Lord and I want to decorate him.

1484
02:34:58,320 --> 02:35:00,620
Hiya, general!

1485
02:35:38,620 --> 02:35:41,120
NARRATOR: Supported by medium bombers and fighter bombers...

1486
02:35:41,520 --> 02:35:43,920
...flying sorties against German positions...

1487
02:35:44,320 --> 02:35:45,820
...elements of the 3rd Army...

1488
02:35:46,120 --> 02:35:48,620
...spearheaded by the 4th Armored Division...

1489
02:35:48,920 --> 02:35:50,420
...drive into Bastogne...

1490
02:35:50,720 --> 02:35:53,120
... to relieve its 18,000 defenders...

1491
02:35:53,420 --> 02:35:55,020
...on the day after Christmas.

1492
02:35:56,120 --> 02:35:59,320
During this operation, 3rd Army moved farther and faster...

1493
02:35:59,720 --> 02:36:02,020
...and engaged more divisions in less time...

1494
02:36:02,420 --> 02:36:05,920
... than any other army in the history of the United States.

1495
02:36:14,352 --> 02:36:16,020
This is the end...

1496
02:36:16,604 --> 02:36:17,939
...the end.

1497
02:36:22,443 --> 02:36:26,989
Hurry, Steiger. I want everything destroyed. Papers, maps, everything!

1498
02:36:27,156 --> 02:36:31,285
Everything will be destroyed, General, that I can promise you.

1499
02:36:31,536 --> 02:36:36,541
I'll never let the Russians take me! I'll kill myself, like the F¨¹hrer!

1500
02:36:39,419 --> 02:36:41,003
He, too, will be destroyed.

1501
02:36:41,337 --> 02:36:45,299
The absence of war will kill him.

1502
02:36:48,177 --> 02:36:50,263
The pure warrior...

1503
02:36:52,849 --> 02:36:55,768
...a magnificent anachronism...

1504
02:37:09,420 --> 02:37:11,720
(MUSlC PLAYS)

1505
02:39:21,820 --> 02:39:23,420
Excuse me, sir.

1506
02:39:23,720 --> 02:39:26,320
General Katkov would like to know if you'll join him. . .

1507
02:39:26,820 --> 02:39:29,420
. . .to drink to the surrender of Germany.

1508
02:39:29,820 --> 02:39:32,020
My compliments to the general.

1509
02:39:32,320 --> 02:39:35,420
Please inform him that I do not care to drink with him. . .

1510
02:39:35,720 --> 02:39:38,320
. . .or any other Russian son of a bitch.

1511
02:39:39,020 --> 02:39:41,120
Sir. . .

1512
02:39:41,420 --> 02:39:43,120
. . .I cannot tell the general that.

1513
02:39:44,720 --> 02:39:46,120
You tell him that.

1514
02:39:46,520 --> 02:39:48,020
Tell him word for word.

1515
02:39:51,920 --> 02:39:58,920
(SPEAKS IN RUSSIAN)

1516
02:40:04,820 --> 02:40:08,720
(SPEAKS IN RUSSIAN)

1517
02:40:10,420 --> 02:40:13,020
The general says he thinks that. . .

1518
02:40:13,420 --> 02:40:15,120
. . .you are a son of a bitch too.

1519
02:40:20,820 --> 02:40:23,720
Okay. I'll drink to that.

1520
02:40:24,020 --> 02:40:25,720
One son of a bitch to another.

1521
02:40:26,120 --> 02:40:30,520
(SPEAKS IN RUSSIAN)

1522
02:40:38,420 --> 02:40:40,920
(CHEERING)

1523
02:41:08,520 --> 02:41:10,720
Is it true that Roosevelt, before he died. . .

1524
02:41:11,020 --> 02:41:13,120
. . .promised you a command in the Pacific?

1525
02:41:13,520 --> 02:41:18,020
Yes. But now that he's gone, I don't think there's much chance of that.

1526
02:41:18,520 --> 02:41:20,620
Doug MacArthur doesn't want me up there.

1527
02:41:20,920 --> 02:41:23,920
We're told of "wonder weapons" the Germans were working on:

1528
02:41:24,320 --> 02:41:26,720
Long-range rockets, push-button bombing. . .

1529
02:41:27,020 --> 02:41:29,320
. . .weapons that don't need soldiers.

1530
02:41:29,820 --> 02:41:31,120
"Wonder weapon"?

1531
02:41:32,020 --> 02:41:34,320
My God, I don't see the wonder in them.

1532
02:41:35,120 --> 02:41:39,120
Killing without heroics. Nothing is glorified, nothing is reaffirmed.

1533
02:41:39,920 --> 02:41:43,320
No heroes, no cowards, no troops.

1534
02:41:43,620 --> 02:41:45,220
No generals.

1535
02:41:45,920 --> 02:41:49,020
Only those that are left alive and those that are left. . .

1536
02:41:49,520 --> 02:41:50,820
. . .dead.

1537
02:41:51,220 --> 02:41:53,020
I'm glad I won't live to see it.

1538
02:41:53,320 --> 02:41:56,820
REPORTER: It's said you're still using former Nazis in key positions.

1539
02:41:57,320 --> 02:41:59,420
Despite the denazification policy.

1540
02:41:59,720 --> 02:42:02,620
Well, if I'm supplied with trained personnel. . .

1541
02:42:02,920 --> 02:42:04,520
. . .I'll get rid of the Nazis.

1542
02:42:04,820 --> 02:42:08,620
Until then, I'll use them to keep the railroads and telephones working.

1543
02:42:09,120 --> 02:42:12,220
After all, didn't most ordinary Nazis join the Party. . .

1544
02:42:12,620 --> 02:42:16,720
. . .in about the same way Americans become Republicans or Democrats?

1545
02:42:17,220 --> 02:42:18,620
Yes, that's about it.

1546
02:42:22,120 --> 02:42:26,620
You agree that national policy be made by civilians, not by the military?

1547
02:42:27,320 --> 02:42:30,220
Of course. But the politicians never let us finish.

1548
02:42:30,620 --> 02:42:33,720
They always stop short and leave us with another war.

1549
02:42:34,520 --> 02:42:36,820
You thinking about our Russian allies?

1550
02:42:41,820 --> 02:42:45,720
Did you say if you found your army between the Germans and the Russians. . .

1551
02:42:46,220 --> 02:42:47,920
. . .you'd attack in both directions?

1552
02:42:48,320 --> 02:42:50,420
No, I never said that.

1553
02:42:51,320 --> 02:42:52,920
I never said any such thing.

1554
02:42:53,620 --> 02:42:55,120
But I wish I had.

1555
02:42:55,420 --> 02:42:56,220
(LAUGHING)

1556
02:43:09,820 --> 02:43:13,720
Sir, there's a call on your line from supreme headquarters, General Smith.

1557
02:43:19,320 --> 02:43:20,220
Bedell?

1558
02:43:20,920 --> 02:43:22,620
Ike is furious.

1559
02:43:22,920 --> 02:43:27,220
How could you compare Republicans and Democrats to the Nazi Party?

1560
02:43:27,720 --> 02:43:29,720
And the statement that you refuse to denazify. . .

1561
02:43:30,120 --> 02:43:32,720
. . .has the Russians, the British, everybody, screaming.

1562
02:43:33,320 --> 02:43:35,920
Well, the hell with the Mongoloid Russians.

1563
02:43:36,220 --> 02:43:39,120
We've given them Berlin, Prague, God knows what else.

1564
02:43:39,420 --> 02:43:41,220
They gonna dictate policy too?

1565
02:43:41,520 --> 02:43:43,620
George, don't be a fool.

1566
02:43:44,020 --> 02:43:47,220
The war in Europe is over. Washington dictates policy.

1567
02:43:47,620 --> 02:43:51,820
The war shouldn't be over. We should stop pussyfooting about the Russians!

1568
02:43:52,220 --> 02:43:56,020
We'll have to fight them anyway. Why not do it now, when the army's here?

1569
02:43:56,520 --> 02:44:00,120
lnstead of disarming Germans let's get them to help fight the Bolsheviks.

1570
02:44:00,820 --> 02:44:03,120
You better shut up. This line may be tapped.

1571
02:44:03,420 --> 02:44:05,120
I don't care. I'll tell you. . .

1572
02:44:05,420 --> 02:44:07,420
. . .we've been fighting the wrong people.

1573
02:44:07,820 --> 02:44:11,120
You and I don't have to get involved, you're so soft about it.

1574
02:44:11,520 --> 02:44:14,720
Leave it to me. In 1 0 days I'll have us at war with them. . .

1575
02:44:15,020 --> 02:44:16,920
. . .and make it look like their fault!

1576
02:44:17,420 --> 02:44:20,520
George, you're mad. You're absolutely out of your mind!

1577
02:44:20,820 --> 02:44:22,420
Well, I'm no diplomat.

1578
02:44:22,820 --> 02:44:25,320
I'm a combat soldier. That's all they understand.

1579
02:44:25,820 --> 02:44:29,420
Get Ike to give me the word, and I'll kick them back to Russia!

1580
02:44:39,120 --> 02:44:41,220
Shall I call the artist back, sir?

1581
02:44:43,020 --> 02:44:45,020
Oh, the hell with it.

1582
02:44:46,720 --> 02:44:50,120
Nobody wants to see a picture of me. I'm mad!

1583
02:44:51,220 --> 02:44:52,720
Don't you know that?

1584
02:45:39,920 --> 02:45:42,720
Field Marshal Montgomery, his majesty is prepared. . .

1585
02:45:43,220 --> 02:45:46,520
. . .to receive the next chief of the imperial general staff.

1586
02:45:59,620 --> 02:46:01,120
Thank you.

1587
02:46:02,120 --> 02:46:03,620
Thank you.

1588
02:46:04,420 --> 02:46:05,820
Take care of yourself.

1589
02:46:06,220 --> 02:46:07,420
George.

1590
02:46:20,620 --> 02:46:23,420
Well, gentlemen. . .

1591
02:46:25,220 --> 02:46:28,420
. . .all good things must come to an end.

1592
02:46:30,920 --> 02:46:33,620
And the best thing that's happened to me. . .

1593
02:46:34,720 --> 02:46:36,220
. . .in my life. . .

1594
02:46:38,120 --> 02:46:40,120
. . .has been. . .

1595
02:46:43,320 --> 02:46:44,620
. . .uh. . .

1596
02:46:45,320 --> 02:46:47,020
. . .the honor. . .

1597
02:46:47,620 --> 02:46:50,520
. . .and privilege. . .

1598
02:46:52,820 --> 02:46:54,920
. . .of commanding the 3rd Army.

1599
02:46:57,920 --> 02:46:59,120
Goodbye. . .

1600
02:47:00,420 --> 02:47:01,920
. . .and God bless you.

1601
02:47:28,520 --> 02:47:30,420
Brad. . .

1602
02:47:30,820 --> 02:47:33,220
. . .they've taken the 3rd Army away from me.

1603
02:47:33,420 --> 02:47:34,620
I know.

1604
02:47:35,420 --> 02:47:38,220
I thought we could have dinner together tonight.

1605
02:47:40,020 --> 02:47:42,920
Thank you, Brad.

1606
02:47:43,220 --> 02:47:45,520
That's damn thoughtful. I appreciate it.

1607
02:47:53,020 --> 02:47:55,420
Right now, I think I'll take Willie for a walk.

1608
02:48:03,020 --> 02:48:04,820
George, look out!

1609
02:48:12,220 --> 02:48:14,620
After all I've been through. . .

1610
02:48:15,020 --> 02:48:17,620
. . .imagine getting killed by an oxcart.

1611
02:48:19,120 --> 02:48:23,520
No, Brad, there's only one proper way for a professional soldier to die.

1612
02:48:23,920 --> 02:48:27,820
That's from the last bullet of the last battle of the last war.

1613
02:48:29,020 --> 02:48:32,220
At least the 3rd Army earned its pay.

1614
02:48:33,220 --> 02:48:35,820
In our drive across Europe, we liberated. . .

1615
02:48:36,120 --> 02:48:38,120
. . . 1 2,000 cities and towns. . .

1616
02:48:38,420 --> 02:48:41,120
. . .and inflicted a million and a half enemy casualties.

1617
02:48:41,620 --> 02:48:45,220
I sense from now on, just being a good soldier won't mean a thing.

1618
02:48:45,520 --> 02:48:50,120
I'm afraid we're gonna have to be diplomats, administrators, you name it.

1619
02:48:50,620 --> 02:48:52,120
God help us.

1620
02:48:57,420 --> 02:49:00,420
George, I want to say one thing.

1621
02:49:01,920 --> 02:49:04,620
You've done a magnificent job here in Europe.

1622
02:49:05,520 --> 02:49:06,920
That's right, George.

1623
02:49:07,720 --> 02:49:12,620
That soldier you slapped did more to win the war than any other private.

1624
02:49:15,920 --> 02:49:17,620
I'll see you for dinner.

1625
02:49:18,020 --> 02:49:19,420
Six-thirty?

1626
02:49:36,020 --> 02:49:37,720
PATTON: For over a thousand years...

1627
02:49:38,020 --> 02:49:40,920
...Roman conquerors returning from the wars...

1628
02:49:41,320 --> 02:49:45,720
...enjoyed the honor of a triumph, a tumultuous parade.

1629
02:49:46,920 --> 02:49:50,820
In the procession came trumpeters and musicians and strange animals...

1630
02:49:51,120 --> 02:49:52,920
...from the conquered territories...

1631
02:49:54,020 --> 02:49:58,020
... together with carts laden with treasure and captured armaments.

1632
02:49:59,320 --> 02:50:02,820
The conqueror rode in a triumphal chariot...

1633
02:50:03,120 --> 02:50:06,220
... the dazed prisoners walking in chains before him.

1634
02:50:07,320 --> 02:50:10,020
Sometimes, his children, robed in white...

1635
02:50:10,320 --> 02:50:13,720
...stood with him in the chariot, or rode the trace horses.

1636
02:50:15,020 --> 02:50:17,820
A slave stood behind the conqueror...

1637
02:50:18,320 --> 02:50:20,820
...holding a golden crown...

1638
02:50:21,620 --> 02:50:24,320
...and whispering in his ear a warning...

1639
02:50:24,920 --> 02:50:26,720
... that all glory...

1640
02:50:27,620 --> 02:50:29,320
...is fleeting.
